# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: huggingface-transformers
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:huggingface-transformers/bert-language-model] BERT is trained by masked token prediction and next sentence prediction.
[src:huggingface-transformers/bert-language-model] With this training, BERT learns contextual, latent representations of tokens in their context, similar to ELMo and GPT-2.
[src:huggingface-transformers/bert-language-model] It found applications for many natural language processing tasks, such as coreference resolution and polysemy resolution.
[src:huggingface-transformers/bert-language-model] It improved on ELMo and spawned the study of "BERTology", which attempts to interpret what is learned by BERT.
[src:huggingface-transformers/bert-language-model] BERT was originally implemented in the English language at two model sizes, BERTBASE (110 million parameters) and BERTLARGE (340 million parameters).
[src:huggingface-transformers/bert-language-model] Both were trained on the Toronto BookCorpus (800M words) and English Wikipedia (2,500M words).
[src:huggingface-transformers/bert-language-model] On March 11, 2020, 24 smaller models were released, the smallest being BERTTINY with just 4 million parameters.
[src:huggingface-transformers/bert-language-model] BERT is an "encoder-only" transformer architecture.
[src:huggingface-transformers/bert-language-model] The task head is necessary for pre-training, but it is often unnecessary for so-called "downstream tasks," such as question answering or sentiment classification.
[src:huggingface-transformers/bert-language-model] Instead, one removes the task head and replaces it with a newly initialized module suited for the task, and finetune the new module.
[src:huggingface-transformers/bert-language-model] The latent vector representation of the model is directly fed into this new module, allowing for sample-efficient transfer learning.
[src:huggingface-transformers/bert-language-model] This section describes the embedding used by BERTBASE.
[src:huggingface-transformers/bert-language-model] The other one, BERTLARGE, is similar, just larger.
[src:huggingface-transformers/bert-language-model] The tokenizer of BERT is WordPiece, which is a sub-word strategy like byte-pair encoding.
[src:huggingface-transformers/bert-language-model] Its vocabulary size is 30,000, and any token not appearing in its vocabulary is replaced by `[UNK]` ("unknown").
[src:huggingface-transformers/bert-language-model] The first layer is the embedding layer, which contains three components: token type embeddings, position embeddings, and segment type embeddings.
[src:huggingface-transformers/bert-language-model] The three embedding vectors are added together representing the initial token representation as a function of these three pieces of information.
[src:huggingface-transformers/bert-language-model] After embedding, the vector representation is normalized using a LayerNorm operation, outputting a 768-dimensional vector for each input token.
[src:huggingface-transformers/bert-language-model] After this, the representation vectors are passed forward through 12 Transformer encoder blocks, and are decoded back to 30,000-dimensional vocabulary space using a basic affine transformation layer.
[src:huggingface-transformers/bert-language-model] The encoder stack of BERT has 2 free parameters: L , the number of layers, and H , the *hidden size*.
[src:huggingface-transformers/bert-language-model] There are always $H/64$ self-attention heads, and the feed-forward/filter size is always $4H$ .
[src:huggingface-transformers/bert-language-model] By varying these two numbers, one obtains an entire family of BERT models.
[src:huggingface-transformers/bert-language-model] The notation for encoder stack is written as L/H.
[src:huggingface-transformers/bert-language-model] For example, BERTBASE is written as 12L/768H, BERTLARGE as 24L/1024H, and BERTTINY as 2L/128H.
[src:huggingface-transformers/bert-language-model] In masked language modeling, 15% of tokens would be randomly selected for masked-prediction task, and the training objective was to predict the masked token given its context.
[src:huggingface-transformers/bert-language-model] The reason not all selected tokens are masked is to avoid the dataset shift problem.
[src:huggingface-transformers/bert-language-model] The dataset shift problem arises when the distribution of inputs seen during training differs significantly from the distribution encountered during inference.
[src:huggingface-transformers/bert-language-model] A trained BERT model might be applied to word representation (like Word2Vec), where it would be run over sentences not containing any `[MASK]` tokens.
[src:huggingface-transformers/bert-language-model] It is later found that more diverse training objectives are generally better.
[src:huggingface-transformers/bert-language-model] As an illustrative example, consider the sentence "my dog is cute".
[src:huggingface-transformers/bert-language-model] It would first be divided into tokens like "my1 dog2 is3 cute4".
[src:huggingface-transformers/bert-language-model] Then a random token in the sentence would be picked.
[src:huggingface-transformers/bert-language-model] After processing the input text, the model's 4th output vector is passed to its decoder layer, which outputs a probability distribution over its 30,000-dimensional vocabulary space.
[src:huggingface-transformers/bert-language-model] Given two sentences, the model predicts if they appear sequentially in the training corpus, outputting either `[IsNext]` or `[NotNext]`.
[src:huggingface-transformers/bert-language-model] During training, the algorithm sometimes samples two sentences from a single continuous span in the training corpus, while at other times, it samples two sentences from two discontinuous spans.
[src:huggingface-transformers/bert-language-model] The first sentence starts with a special token, `[CLS]` (for "classify").
[src:huggingface-transformers/bert-language-model] The two sentences are separated by another special token, `[SEP]` (for "separate").
[src:huggingface-transformers/bert-language-model] After processing the two sentences, the final vector for the `[CLS]` token is passed to a linear layer for binary classification into `[IsNext]` and `[NotNext]`.
[src:huggingface-transformers/bert-language-model] BERT is meant as a general pretrained model for various applications in natural language processing.
[src:huggingface-transformers/bert-language-model] In the original paper, all parameters of BERT are fine-tuned, and recommended that, for downstream applications that are text classifications, the output token at the `[CLS]` input token is fed into a linear-softmax layer to produce the label outputs.
[src:huggingface-transformers/bert-language-model] The original code base defined the final linear layer as a "pooler layer", in analogy with global pooling in computer vision, even though it simply discards all output tokens except the one corresponding to `[CLS]`.
[src:huggingface-transformers/bert-language-model] BERT was trained on the BookCorpus (800M words) and a filtered version of English Wikipedia (2,500M words) without lists, tables, and headers.
[src:huggingface-transformers/bert-language-model] Training BERTBASE on 4 cloud TPU (16 TPU chips total) took 4 days, at an estimated cost of 500 USD.
[src:huggingface-transformers/bert-language-model] Training BERTLARGE on 16 cloud TPU (64 TPU chips total) took 4 days.
[src:huggingface-transformers/bert-language-model] Language models like ELMo, GPT-2, and BERT, spawned the study of "BERTology", which attempts to interpret what is learned by these models.
[src:huggingface-transformers/bert-language-model] Their performance on these natural language understanding tasks are not yet well understood.
[src:huggingface-transformers/bert-language-model] Several research publications in 2018 and 2019 focused on investigating the relationship behind BERT's output as a result of carefully chosen input sequences, analysis of internal vector representations through probing classifiers, and the relationships represented by attention weights.
[src:huggingface-transformers/bert-language-model] The high performance of the BERT model could also be attributed to the fact that it is bidirectionally trained.
[src:huggingface-transformers/bert-language-model] This means that BERT, based on the Transformer model architecture, applies its self-attention mechanism to learn information from a text from the left and right side during training, and consequently gains a deep understanding of the context.
[src:huggingface-transformers/bert-language-model] For example, the word *fine* can have two different meanings depending on the context (**I feel** fine **today**, **She has** fine **blond hair**).
[src:huggingface-transformers/bert-language-model] BERT considers the words surrounding the target word *fine* from the left and right side.
[src:huggingface-transformers/bert-language-model] However it comes at a cost: due to encoder-only architecture lacking a decoder, BERT can't be prompted and can't generate text, while bidirectional models in general do not work effectively without the right side, thus being difficult to prompt.
[src:huggingface-transformers/bert-language-model] As an illustrative example, if one wishes to use BERT to continue a sentence fragment "Today, I went to", then naively one would mask out all the tokens as "Today, I went to `[MASK]` `[MASK]` `[MASK]` ...
[src:huggingface-transformers/bert-language-model] `[MASK]` ." where the number of `[MASK]` is the length of the sentence one wishes to extend to.
[src:huggingface-transformers/bert-language-model] However, this constitutes a dataset shift, as during training, BERT has never seen sentences with that many tokens masked out.
[src:huggingface-transformers/bert-language-model] More sophisticated techniques allow text generation, but at a high computational cost.
[src:huggingface-transformers/bert-language-model] BERT was originally published by Google researchers Jacob Devlin, Ming-Wei Chang, Kenton Lee, and Kristina Toutanova.
[src:huggingface-transformers/bert-language-model] The design has its origins from pre-training contextual representations, including semi-supervised sequence learning, generative pre-training, ELMo, and ULMFit.
[src:huggingface-transformers/bert-language-model] Unlike previous models, BERT is a deeply bidirectional, unsupervised language representation, pre-trained using only a plain text corpus.
[src:huggingface-transformers/bert-language-model] Context-free models such as word2vec or GloVe generate a single word embedding representation for each word in the vocabulary, whereas BERT takes into account the context for each occurrence of a given word.
[src:huggingface-transformers/bert-language-model] For instance, whereas the vector for "running" will have the same word2vec vector representation for both of its occurrences in the sentences "He is running a company" and "He is running a marathon", BERT will provide a contextualized embedding that will be different according to the sentence.
[src:huggingface-transformers/bert-language-model] On October 25, 2019, Google announced that they had started applying BERT models to English-language search queries on Google Search within the US.
[src:huggingface-transformers/bert-language-model] On December 9, 2019, it was reported that BERT had been adopted by Google Search for over 70 languages.
[src:huggingface-transformers/bert-language-model] In October 2020, almost every single English-based query was processed by a BERT model.
[src:huggingface-transformers/bert-language-model] The BERT models were influential and inspired many variants.
[src:huggingface-transformers/bert-language-model] The three attention matrices are added together element-wise, then passed through a softmax layer and multiplied by a projection matrix.
[src:huggingface-transformers/bert-language-model] Absolute position encoding is included in the final self-attention layer as additional input.
[src:huggingface-transformers/fine-tuning-deep-learning] In deep learning, **fine-tuning** is the process of adapting a computational model trained for one task (the *upstream task*) to perform a different, usually more specific, task (the *downstream task*).
[src:huggingface-transformers/fine-tuning-deep-learning] It is considered a form of transfer learning, as it reuses knowledge learned from the original training objective.
[src:huggingface-transformers/fine-tuning-deep-learning] Fine-tuning involves applying additional training (e.g., on new data) to the parameters of a neural network that have been pre-trained.
[src:huggingface-transformers/fine-tuning-deep-learning] The additional training can be applied to the entire neural network, or to only a subset of its layers, in which case the layers that are not being fine-tuned are "frozen" (i.e., not changed during backpropagation).
[src:huggingface-transformers/fine-tuning-deep-learning] A model may also be augmented with "adapters"—lightweight modules inserted into the model's architecture that nudge the embedding space for domain adaptation.
[src:huggingface-transformers/fine-tuning-deep-learning] These contain far fewer parameters than the original model and can be fine-tuned in a parameter-efficient way by tuning only their weights and leaving the rest of the model's weights frozen.
[src:huggingface-transformers/fine-tuning-deep-learning] Models that are pre-trained on large, general corpora are usually fine-tuned by reusing their parameters as a starting point and adding a task-specific layer trained from scratch.
[src:huggingface-transformers/fine-tuning-deep-learning] Fine-tuning the full model is also common and often yields better results, but is more computationally expensive.
[src:huggingface-transformers/fine-tuning-deep-learning] Fine-tuning is typically accomplished via supervised learning, but there are also techniques to fine-tune a model using weak supervision.
[src:huggingface-transformers/fine-tuning-deep-learning] Fine-tuning can be combined with a reinforcement learning from human feedback-based objective to produce language models such as ChatGPT (a fine-tuned version of GPT models) and Sparrow.
[src:huggingface-transformers/fine-tuning-deep-learning] Fine-tuning can degrade a model's robustness to distribution shifts.
[src:huggingface-transformers/fine-tuning-deep-learning] One mitigation is to linearly interpolate a fine-tuned model's weights with the weights of the original model, which can greatly increase out-of-distribution performance while largely retaining the in-distribution performance of the fine-tuned model.
[src:huggingface-transformers/fine-tuning-deep-learning] Low-rank adaptation (LoRA) is an adapter-based technique for efficiently fine-tuning models.
[src:huggingface-transformers/fine-tuning-deep-learning] The basic idea is to design a low-rank matrix that is then added to the original matrix.
[src:huggingface-transformers/fine-tuning-deep-learning] An adapter, in this context, is a collection of low-rank matrices which, when added to a base model, produces a fine-tuned model.
[src:huggingface-transformers/fine-tuning-deep-learning] It allows for performance that approaches full-model fine-tuning with lower space requirements.
[src:huggingface-transformers/fine-tuning-deep-learning] A language model with billions of parameters may be LoRA fine-tuned with only several millions of parameters.
[src:huggingface-transformers/fine-tuning-deep-learning] LoRA-based fine-tuning has become popular in the Stable Diffusion community.
[src:huggingface-transformers/fine-tuning-deep-learning] Support for LoRA was integrated into the diffusers library from Hugging Face.
[src:huggingface-transformers/fine-tuning-deep-learning] Support for LoRA and similar techniques is also available for a wide range of other models through Hugging Face's *parameter-efficient fine-tuning (PEFT)* package.
[src:huggingface-transformers/fine-tuning-deep-learning] Representation fine-tuning (ReFT) is a technique developed by researchers at Stanford University aimed at fine-tuning large language models (LLMs) by modifying less than 1% of their representations.
[src:huggingface-transformers/fine-tuning-deep-learning] Unlike parameter-efficient fine-tuning (PEFT) methods, which mainly focus on updating weights, ReFT targets representations.
[src:huggingface-transformers/fine-tuning-deep-learning] ReFT methods operate on a frozen base model and learn task-specific interventions on hidden representations and train interventions that manipulate a small fraction of model representations to steer model behaviors towards solving downstream tasks at inference time.
[src:huggingface-transformers/fine-tuning-deep-learning] One specific method within the ReFT family is low-rank linear subspace ReFT (LoReFT), which intervenes on hidden representations in the linear subspace spanned by a low-rank projection matrix.
[src:huggingface-transformers/fine-tuning-deep-learning] LoReFT can be seen as the representation-based equivalent of low-rank adaptation (LoRA).
[src:huggingface-transformers/fine-tuning-deep-learning] Fine-tuning is common in natural language processing (NLP), especially in the domain of language modeling.
[src:huggingface-transformers/fine-tuning-deep-learning] Large language models like OpenAI's series of GPT foundation models can be fine-tuned on data for specific downstream NLP tasks (tasks that use a pre-trained model) to improve performance over the unmodified pre-trained model.
[src:huggingface-transformers/fine-tuning-deep-learning] Platforms such as Semrush's *AI Visibility Toolkit* and *Enterprise AIO* exemplify how fine-tuned models are being used for entity-level monitoring; tracking how named entities are referenced and represented within responses generated by large-language-model-based answer engines.
[src:huggingface-transformers/fine-tuning-deep-learning] Commercially-offered large language models can sometimes be fine-tuned if the provider offers a fine-tuning API.
[src:huggingface-transformers/fine-tuning-deep-learning] As of June 19, 2023, language model fine-tuning APIs are offered by OpenAI and Microsoft Azure's Azure OpenAI Service for a subset of their models, as well as by Google Cloud Platform for some of their PaLM models, and by others.
[src:huggingface-transformers/generative-pre-trained-transformer] A **generative pre-trained transformer** (**GPT**) is a type of large language model (LLM) that is widely used in generative artificial intelligence chatbots.
[src:huggingface-transformers/generative-pre-trained-transformer] GPTs are based on a deep learning architecture called the transformer.
[src:huggingface-transformers/generative-pre-trained-transformer] They are pre-trained on large datasets of unlabeled content, and able to generate novel content.
[src:huggingface-transformers/generative-pre-trained-transformer] OpenAI was the first to apply generative pre-training to the transformer architecture, introducing the GPT-1 model in 2018.
[src:huggingface-transformers/generative-pre-trained-transformer] The company has since released many bigger GPT models.
[src:huggingface-transformers/generative-pre-trained-transformer] The chatbot ChatGPT, released in late 2022 (using GPT-3.5), was followed by many competitor chatbots using their own generative pre-trained transformers to generate text, such as Gemini, DeepSeek and Claude.
[src:huggingface-transformers/generative-pre-trained-transformer] GPTs are primarily used to generate text, but can be trained to generate other kinds of data.
[src:huggingface-transformers/generative-pre-trained-transformer] For example, GPT-4o can process and generate text, images and audio.
[src:huggingface-transformers/generative-pre-trained-transformer] To improve performance on complex tasks, some GPTs, such as OpenAI o3, allocate more computation time analyzing the problem before generating an output, and are called reasoning models.
[src:huggingface-transformers/generative-pre-trained-transformer] In 2025, GPT-5 was released with a router that automatically selects whether to use a faster model or slower reasoning model based on the provided task.
[src:huggingface-transformers/generative-pre-trained-transformer] During the 2010s, improved machine learning algorithms, more powerful computers, and an increase in the amount of digitized material allowed for an AI boom.
[src:huggingface-transformers/generative-pre-trained-transformer] Separately, the concept of generative pre-training (GP) was a long-established technique in machine learning.
[src:huggingface-transformers/generative-pre-trained-transformer] GP is a form of self-supervised learning wherein a model is first trained on a large, unlabeled dataset (the "pre-training" step) to learn to generate data points.
[src:huggingface-transformers/generative-pre-trained-transformer] This pre-trained model is then adapted to a specific task using a labeled dataset (the "fine-tuning" step).
[src:huggingface-transformers/generative-pre-trained-transformer] The transformer architecture for deep learning is the core technology of a GPT.
[src:huggingface-transformers/generative-pre-trained-transformer] Developed by researchers at Google, it was introduced in the paper "Attention Is All You Need", which was released in 2017.
[src:huggingface-transformers/generative-pre-trained-transformer] The transformer architecture solved many of the performance issues that were associated with older recurrent neural network (RNN) designs for natural language processing (NLP).
[src:huggingface-transformers/generative-pre-trained-transformer] The architecture's use of an attention mechanism allows models to process entire sequences of text at once, enabling the training of much larger and more sophisticated models.
[src:huggingface-transformers/generative-pre-trained-transformer] Since 2017, available transformer-based NLP systems have been capable of processing, mining, organizing, connecting, contrasting, and summarizing texts as well as answering questions from textual input.
[src:huggingface-transformers/generative-pre-trained-transformer] On June 11, 2018, OpenAI researchers and engineers published a paper called "Improving Language Understanding by Generative Pre-Training", which introduced GPT-1, the first GPT model.
[src:huggingface-transformers/generative-pre-trained-transformer] It was designed as a transformer-based large language model that used generative pre-training (GP) on BookCorpus, a diverse text corpus, followed by discriminative fine-tuning to focus on specific language tasks.
[src:huggingface-transformers/generative-pre-trained-transformer] This semi-supervised approach was seen as a breakthrough.
[src:huggingface-transformers/generative-pre-trained-transformer] GPT models use only the decoder part of the transformer architecture, pre-trained to predict the next token in a sequence.
[src:huggingface-transformers/generative-pre-trained-transformer] Previously, the best-performing neural models in natural language processing (NLP) had commonly employed supervised learning from large amounts of manually labeled data – training a large language model with this approach would have been prohibitively expensive and time-consuming.
[src:huggingface-transformers/generative-pre-trained-transformer] On February 14, 2019, OpenAI introduced GPT-2, a larger model that could generate coherent text.
[src:huggingface-transformers/generative-pre-trained-transformer] Created as a direct scale-up of its predecessor, it had both its parameter count and dataset size increased by a factor of 10.
[src:huggingface-transformers/generative-pre-trained-transformer] GPT-2 has 1.5 billion parameters and was trained on WebText, a 40-gigabyte dataset of 8 million web pages.
[src:huggingface-transformers/generative-pre-trained-transformer] Citing risks of malicious use, OpenAI opted for a "staged release", initially publishing smaller versions of the model before releasing the full 1.5-billion-parameter model in November.
[src:huggingface-transformers/generative-pre-trained-transformer] On May 28, 2020, OpenAI introduced GPT-3, a model with 175 billion parameters that was trained on a larger dataset compared to GPT-2.
[src:huggingface-transformers/generative-pre-trained-transformer] It marked a significant advancement in few-shot and zero-shot learning abilities.
[src:huggingface-transformers/generative-pre-trained-transformer] With few examples, it could perform various tasks that it was not explicitly trained for.
[src:huggingface-transformers/generative-pre-trained-transformer] Following the release of GPT-3, OpenAI started using reinforcement learning from human feedback (RLHF) to align models' behavior more closely with human preferences.
[src:huggingface-transformers/generative-pre-trained-transformer] This led to the development of InstructGPT, a fine-tuned version of GPT-3.
[src:huggingface-transformers/generative-pre-trained-transformer] OpenAI further refined InstructGPT to create ChatGPT, the flagship chatbot product of OpenAI that was launched on November 30, 2022.
[src:huggingface-transformers/generative-pre-trained-transformer] ChatGPT was initially based on GPT-3.5, but it was later transitioned to the GPT-4 model, which was released on March 14, 2023.
[src:huggingface-transformers/generative-pre-trained-transformer] GPT-4 was also integrated into parts of several applications, including Microsoft Copilot, GitHub Copilot, Snapchat, Khan Academy, and Duolingo.
[src:huggingface-transformers/generative-pre-trained-transformer] The immense popularity of ChatGPT spurred widespread development of competing GPT-based systems from other organizations.
[src:huggingface-transformers/generative-pre-trained-transformer] EleutherAI released a series of open-weight models, including GPT-J in 2021.
[src:huggingface-transformers/generative-pre-trained-transformer] Other major technology companies later developed their own GPT models, such as Google's PaLM and Gemini as well as Meta AI's Llama.
[src:huggingface-transformers/generative-pre-trained-transformer] Many subsequent GPT models have been trained to be multimodal (able to process or to generate multiple types of data).
[src:huggingface-transformers/generative-pre-trained-transformer] For example, GPT-4o can both process and generate text, images, and audio.
[src:huggingface-transformers/generative-pre-trained-transformer] Additionally, GPT models like o3 and DeepSeek R1 have been trained with reinforcement learning to generate multi-step chain-of-thought reasoning before producing a final answer, which helps to solve complex problems in domains such as mathematics.
[src:huggingface-transformers/generative-pre-trained-transformer] On August 7, 2025, OpenAI released GPT-5, which includes a router that automatically selects whether to use a faster model or slower reasoning model based on task.
[src:huggingface-transformers/generative-pre-trained-transformer] A foundation model is an AI model trained on broad data at scale such that it can be adapted to a wide range of downstream tasks.
[src:huggingface-transformers/generative-pre-trained-transformer] The most recent OpenAI's *GPT-n* series model is GPT-5.
[src:huggingface-transformers/generative-pre-trained-transformer] Meta AI (formerly Facebook) also has a generative transformer-based foundational large language model, known as LLaMA.
[src:huggingface-transformers/generative-pre-trained-transformer] Foundational GPTs can also employ modalities other than text, for input and/or output.
[src:huggingface-transformers/generative-pre-trained-transformer] GPT-4 is a multi-modal LLM that is capable of processing text and image input (though its output is limited to text).
[src:huggingface-transformers/generative-pre-trained-transformer] Regarding multimodal *output*, some generative transformer-based models are used for text-to-image technologies such as diffusion and parallel decoding.
[src:huggingface-transformers/generative-pre-trained-transformer] Such kinds of models can serve as visual foundation models (VFMs) for developing downstream systems that can work with images.
[src:huggingface-transformers/generative-pre-trained-transformer] The computational and memory requirements of transformer-based models increase significantly as they scale to larger sizes and longer input sequences.
[src:huggingface-transformers/generative-pre-trained-transformer] The standard self-attention mechanism has a quadratic complexity with respect to input sequence length, as described in *Attention Is All You Need*.
[src:huggingface-transformers/generative-pre-trained-transformer] Researchers proposed a number of efficiency improvements like sparse attention mechanisms and memory-efficient architectures that reduce computational costs while supporting longer context windows.
[src:huggingface-transformers/generative-pre-trained-transformer] Models like BigBird, Reformer, and FlashAttention demonstrate structured attention patterns or optimized computation to improve scalability and efficiency.
[src:huggingface-transformers/generative-pre-trained-transformer] This has helped large language models to efficiently process long input sequences with reduced memory and computation during both training and inference.
[src:huggingface-transformers/generative-pre-trained-transformer] Scaling laws describe empirical relationships between the performance of large language models and factors such as model size, dataset size, and computational resources.
[src:huggingface-transformers/generative-pre-trained-transformer] Empirical work has found that performance tends to follow approximate power-law relationships as these factors increase.
[src:huggingface-transformers/generative-pre-trained-transformer] Larger models trained on more data generally achieve lower training loss and better generalization.
[src:huggingface-transformers/generative-pre-trained-transformer] Later work suggests that performance is not determined by parameter count alone, but by how model size, data, and compute are balanced during training.
[src:huggingface-transformers/generative-pre-trained-transformer] These observations have influenced the development of successive GPT models, particularly in decisions about architecture design, dataset composition, and training strategies.
[src:huggingface-transformers/generative-pre-trained-transformer] Emergent abilities refer to capabilities that appear in large language models only when they reach a certain scale and are not present in smaller versions of the same models.
[src:huggingface-transformers/generative-pre-trained-transformer] These abilities are considered "emergent" because they arise as model size, training data, and compute increase.
[src:huggingface-transformers/generative-pre-trained-transformer] Examples of emergent abilities include multi-step reasoning, in-context learning (the ability to perform tasks based on examples provided in prompts without additional training), and improved performance on complex language and reasoning benchmarks.
[src:huggingface-transformers/generative-pre-trained-transformer] Research suggests that these capabilities do not scale linearly, but instead appear once models exceed certain thresholds in size and training scale.
[src:huggingface-transformers/generative-pre-trained-transformer] This phenomenon has influenced the development of larger GPT models and contributed to their increased effectiveness across a wide range of tasks.
[src:huggingface-transformers/generative-pre-trained-transformer] OpenAI, which created the first generative pre-trained transformer (GPT) in 2018, asserted in 2023 that "GPT" should be regarded as a *brand* of OpenAI.
[src:huggingface-transformers/generative-pre-trained-transformer] In April 2023, OpenAI revised the brand guidelines in its terms of service to indicate that other businesses using its API to run their AI services would no longer be able to include "GPT" in such names or branding.
[src:huggingface-transformers/generative-pre-trained-transformer] In May 2023, OpenAI engaged a brand management service to notify its API customers of this policy, although these notifications stopped short of making overt legal claims (such as allegations of trademark infringement or demands to cease and desist).
[src:huggingface-transformers/generative-pre-trained-transformer] As of November 2023, OpenAI still prohibits its API licensees from naming their own products with "GPT", but it has begun enabling its ChatGPT Plus subscribers to make "custom versions of ChatGPT" called GPTs on the OpenAI site.
[src:huggingface-transformers/generative-pre-trained-transformer] OpenAI's terms of service says that its subscribers may use "GPT" in the names of these, although it's "discouraged".
[src:huggingface-transformers/generative-pre-trained-transformer] Relatedly, OpenAI has applied to the United States Patent and Trademark Office (USPTO) to seek domestic trademark registration for the term "GPT" in the field of AI.
[src:huggingface-transformers/generative-pre-trained-transformer] OpenAI sought to expedite handling of its application, but the USPTO declined that request in April 2023.
[src:huggingface-transformers/generative-pre-trained-transformer] In May 2023, the USPTO responded to the application with a determination that "GPT" was both descriptive and generic.
[src:huggingface-transformers/generative-pre-trained-transformer] As of November 2023, OpenAI continued to pursue its argument.
[src:huggingface-transformers/generative-pre-trained-transformer] For any given type or scope of trademark protection in the U.S., OpenAI would need to establish that the term is actually "distinctive" to their specific offerings in addition to being a broader technical term for the kind of technology.
[src:huggingface-transformers/generative-pre-trained-transformer] Some media reports suggested in 2023 that OpenAI may be able to obtain trademark registration based indirectly on the fame of its GPT-based chatbot product, ChatGPT, for which OpenAI has *separately* sought protection (and which it has sought to enforce more strongly).
[src:huggingface-transformers/generative-pre-trained-transformer] Other reports have indicated that registration for the bare term "GPT" seems unlikely to be granted, as it is used frequently as a common term to refer simply to AI systems that involve generative pre-trained transformers.
[src:huggingface-transformers/generative-pre-trained-transformer] In any event, to whatever extent exclusive rights in the term may occur the U.S., others would need to avoid using it for similar products or services in ways likely to cause confusion.
[src:huggingface-transformers/generative-pre-trained-transformer] If such rights ever became broad enough to implicate other well-established uses in the field, the trademark doctrine of *descriptive fair use* could still continue non-brand-related usage.
[src:huggingface-transformers/generative-pre-trained-transformer] In the European Union, the European Union Intellectual Property Office registered "GPT" as a trade mark of OpenAI in spring 2023.
[src:huggingface-transformers/generative-pre-trained-transformer] However, since spring 2024 the registration is being challenged and is pending cancellation.
[src:huggingface-transformers/generative-pre-trained-transformer] In Switzerland, the Swiss Federal Institute of Intellectual Property registered "GPT" as a trade mark of OpenAI in spring 2023.
[src:huggingface-transformers/generative-pre-trained-transformer] The evaluation of generative pre-trained transformer models is carried out using a range of benchmarks and metrics, which aim to assess their performance across different tasks.
[src:huggingface-transformers/generative-pre-trained-transformer] Common approaches include accuracy on standard datasets, as well as other features such as robustness, bias, and toxicity.
[src:huggingface-transformers/generative-pre-trained-transformer] These models are typically tested on tasks such as natural language understanding, reasoning, answering queries, and code generation.
[src:huggingface-transformers/generative-pre-trained-transformer] Sometimes they combine multiple tasks to provide a broader assessment of model performance across domains.
[src:huggingface-transformers/generative-pre-trained-transformer] More recent approaches extend these evaluations to include other features such as fairness, efficiency, and transparency, in order to get a more accurate assessment of these models.
[src:huggingface-transformers/generative-pre-trained-transformer] Evaluation remains an active area of research, as existing tests may not accurately reflect real-world performance or the risks associated with large-scale generative models.
[src:huggingface-transformers/generative-pre-trained-transformer] Generative pre-trained transformer models have raised a range of ethical and societal concerns, particularly regarding bias, misinformation, and environmental impact.
[src:huggingface-transformers/generative-pre-trained-transformer] Large language models can reproduce and amplify patterns present in their training data, including social biases, which may lead to unfair or misleading outputs.
[src:huggingface-transformers/generative-pre-trained-transformer] These models have also been associated with generating inaccurate or misleading information as they are designed to produce fluent text rather than to verify factual accuracy.
[src:huggingface-transformers/generative-pre-trained-transformer] This has an impact on their use in applications such as automated content generation and information dissemination.
[src:huggingface-transformers/generative-pre-trained-transformer] Training large-scale models also requires huge computational resources, contributing to increased energy consumption and environmental costs.
[src:huggingface-transformers/generative-pre-trained-transformer] Concerns about the environmental impact of large AI systems have led to calls for more efficient training methods and more transparency in reporting resource usage.
[src:huggingface-transformers/hugging-face] The company was founded in 2016 by French entrepreneurs Clément Delangue, Julien Chaumond, and Thomas Wolf in New York City, originally as a company that developed a chatbot app targeted at teenagers.
[src:huggingface-transformers/hugging-face] The company was named after the U+1F917 🤗 HUGGING FACE emoji.
[src:huggingface-transformers/hugging-face] After open sourcing the model behind the chatbot, the company pivoted to focus on being a platform for machine learning.
[src:huggingface-transformers/hugging-face] On April 28, 2021, the company launched the BigScience Research Workshop in collaboration with several other research groups to release an open large language model.
[src:huggingface-transformers/hugging-face] In 2022, the workshop concluded with the announcement of BLOOM, a multilingual large language model with 176 billion parameters.
[src:huggingface-transformers/hugging-face] In February 2023, the company announced partnership with Amazon Web Services (AWS) which would allow Hugging Face's products to be available to AWS customers to use them as the building blocks for their custom applications.
[src:huggingface-transformers/hugging-face] The company also said the next generation of BLOOM will be run on Trainium, a proprietary machine learning chip created by AWS.
[src:huggingface-transformers/hugging-face] In June 2024, the company announced, along with Meta and Scaleway, their launch of a new AI accelerator program for European startups.
[src:huggingface-transformers/hugging-face] The initiative aimed to help startups integrate open foundation models into their products, accelerating the EU AI ecosystem.
[src:huggingface-transformers/hugging-face] The program, based at STATION F in Paris, ran from September 2024 to February 2025.
[src:huggingface-transformers/hugging-face] Selected startups received mentoring, and access to AI models and tools and Scaleway's computing power.
[src:huggingface-transformers/hugging-face] On September 23, 2024, to further the International Decade of Indigenous Languages, Hugging Face teamed up with Meta and UNESCO to launch a new online language translator.
[src:huggingface-transformers/hugging-face] It was built on Meta's No Language Left Behind open-source AI model, enabling free text translation across 200 languages, including many low-resource languages.
[src:huggingface-transformers/hugging-face] In April 2025, Hugging Face announced that they acquired a humanoid robotics startup, Pollen Robotics, based in France and founded by Matthieu Lapeyre and Pierre Rouanet in 2016.
[src:huggingface-transformers/hugging-face] In an X tweet, Delangue shared his vision to "make Artificial Intelligence robotics Open Source".
[src:huggingface-transformers/hugging-face] In early 2026, hackers hijacked the Hugging Face platform to launch Android-targeted attacks involving "powerful malware" which could completely take over a compromised target.
[src:huggingface-transformers/large-language-model-p01] A **large language model** (**LLM**) is a neural network trained on a vast amount of text for natural language processing tasks, especially language generation.
[src:huggingface-transformers/large-language-model-p01] LLMs can typically generate, summarize, translate, and analyze text in many contexts, and are a foundational technology behind modern chatbots.
[src:huggingface-transformers/large-language-model-p01] Biased or inaccurate training data can make an LLM's output less reliable.
[src:huggingface-transformers/large-language-model-p01] LLMs are typically based on transformer architecture.
[src:huggingface-transformers/large-language-model-p01] Generative pre-trained transformers (GPTs) are a type of LLM that is pre-trained to predict the next word.
[src:huggingface-transformers/large-language-model-p01] GPTs are then often fine-tuned to follow instructions and to behave as assistants.
[src:huggingface-transformers/large-language-model-p01] Benchmark evaluations for LLMs attempt to measure model reasoning, factual accuracy, alignment, and safety.
[src:huggingface-transformers/large-language-model-p01] Before the emergence of transformer-based models in 2017, some language models were considered large relative to the computational and data constraints of their time.
[src:huggingface-transformers/large-language-model-p01] In the early 1990s, IBM's statistical models pioneered word alignment techniques for machine translation, laying the groundwork for corpus-based language modeling.
[src:huggingface-transformers/large-language-model-p01] In 2001, a smoothed *n*-gram model, such as those employing Kneser–Ney smoothing, trained on 300 million words, achieved state-of-the-art perplexity on benchmark tests.
[src:huggingface-transformers/large-language-model-p01] During the 2000s, with the rise of widespread internet access, researchers began compiling massive text datasets from the web ("web as corpus") to train statistical language models.
[src:huggingface-transformers/large-language-model-p01] Moving beyond *n*-gram models, researchers started in 2000 to use neural networks as language models.
[src:huggingface-transformers/large-language-model-p01] Following the breakthrough of deep neural networks in image classification around 2012, similar architectures were adapted for language tasks.
[src:huggingface-transformers/large-language-model-p01] This shift was marked by the development of word embeddings (e.g., Word2Vec by Mikolov in 2013) and sequence-to-sequence (seq2seq) models using LSTM.
[src:huggingface-transformers/large-language-model-p01] In 2016, Google transitioned its translation service to neural machine translation (NMT), replacing statistical phrase-based models with deep recurrent neural networks.
[src:huggingface-transformers/large-language-model-p01] These early NMT systems used LSTM-based encoder-decoder architectures, as they preceded the invention of transformers.
[src:huggingface-transformers/large-language-model-p01] At the 2017 NeurIPS conference, Google researchers introduced the transformer architecture in their landmark paper "Attention Is All You Need".
[src:huggingface-transformers/large-language-model-p01] This paper's goal was to improve upon 2014 seq2seq technology, and was based mainly on the attention mechanism developed by Bahdanau et al. in 2014.
[src:huggingface-transformers/large-language-model-p01] The following year in 2018, BERT was introduced and quickly became "ubiquitous".
[src:huggingface-transformers/large-language-model-p01] Though the original transformer has both encoder and decoder blocks, BERT is an encoder-only model.
[src:huggingface-transformers/large-language-model-p01] Academic and research usage of BERT began to decline in 2023, following rapid improvements in the abilities of decoder-only models (such as GPT) to solve tasks via prompting.
[src:huggingface-transformers/large-language-model-p01] Although decoder-only GPT-1 was introduced in 2018, it was GPT-2 in 2019 that caught widespread attention because OpenAI claimed to have initially deemed it too powerful to release publicly, out of fear of malicious use.
[src:huggingface-transformers/large-language-model-p01] GPT-3 in 2020 went a step further and as of 2025 is available only via API with no offering of downloading the model to execute locally.
[src:huggingface-transformers/large-language-model-p01] But it was the consumer-facing chatbot ChatGPT in late 2022 that received extensive media coverage and public attention by 2023.
[src:huggingface-transformers/large-language-model-p01] The 2023 GPT-4 was praised for its increased accuracy and as a "holy grail" for its multimodal capabilities.
[src:huggingface-transformers/large-language-model-p01] OpenAI did not reveal the high-level architecture and the number of parameters of GPT-4.
[src:huggingface-transformers/large-language-model-p01] The release of ChatGPT led to an uptick in LLM usage across several research subfields of computer science, including robotics, software engineering, and societal impact work.
[src:huggingface-transformers/large-language-model-p01] In 2024, OpenAI released the reasoning model OpenAI o1, which generates long chains of thought before returning a final answer.
[src:huggingface-transformers/large-language-model-p01] Many LLMs with parameter counts comparable to those of OpenAI's GPT series have been developed.
[src:huggingface-transformers/large-language-model-p01] Since 2022, weights-available models have been gaining popularity, especially at first with BLOOM and LLaMA, though both have restrictions on usage and deployment.
[src:huggingface-transformers/large-language-model-p01] Mistral AI's open-weight models Mistral 7B and Mixtral 8x7B have a more permissive Apache License.
[src:huggingface-transformers/large-language-model-p01] In January 2025, DeepSeek released DeepSeek R1, a 671-billion-parameter open-weight model that performs comparably to OpenAI o1 but at a much lower price per token for users.
[src:huggingface-transformers/large-language-model-p01] Since 2023, many LLMs have been trained to be multimodal, having the ability to also process or generate other types of data, such as images, audio, or 3D meshes.
[src:huggingface-transformers/large-language-model-p01] Open-weight LLMs have become more influential since 2023.
[src:huggingface-transformers/large-language-model-p01] (2025), community-driven contributions to open-weight models improve their efficiency and performance via collaborative platforms such as Hugging Face.
[src:huggingface-transformers/large-language-model-p01] As machine learning algorithms process numbers rather than text, the text must be converted to numbers.
[src:huggingface-transformers/large-language-model-p01] In the first step, a vocabulary is decided upon, then integer indices are arbitrarily but uniquely assigned to each vocabulary entry, and finally, an embedding is associated with the integer index.
[src:huggingface-transformers/large-language-model-p01] Algorithms include byte-pair encoding (BPE) and WordPiece.
[src:huggingface-transformers/large-language-model-p01] There are also special tokens serving as control characters, such as `[MASK]` for masked-out token (as used in BERT), and `[UNK]` ("unknown") for characters not appearing in the vocabulary.
[src:huggingface-transformers/large-language-model-p01] Also, some special symbols are used to denote special text formatting.
[src:huggingface-transformers/large-language-model-p01] For example, "Ġ" denotes a preceding whitespace in RoBERTa and GPT and "##" denotes continuation of a preceding word in BERT.
[src:huggingface-transformers/large-language-model-p01] Tokenization also compresses the datasets.
[src:huggingface-transformers/large-language-model-p01] Because LLMs generally require input to be an array that is not jagged, the shorter texts must be "padded" until they match the length of the longest one.
[src:huggingface-transformers/large-language-model-p01] As an example, consider a tokenizer based on byte-pair encoding.
[src:huggingface-transformers/large-language-model-p01] In the first step, all unique characters (including blanks and punctuation marks) are treated as an initial set of *n*-grams (i.e. initial set of uni-grams).
[src:huggingface-transformers/large-language-model-p01] Successively the most frequent pair of adjacent characters is merged into a bi-gram and all instances of the pair are replaced by it.
[src:huggingface-transformers/large-language-model-p01] All occurrences of adjacent pairs of (previously merged) *n*-grams that most frequently occur together are then again merged into even lengthier *n*-gram, until a vocabulary of prescribed size is obtained.
[src:huggingface-transformers/large-language-model-p01] After a tokenizer is trained, any text can be tokenized by it, as long as it does not contain characters not appearing in the initial-set of uni-grams.
[src:huggingface-transformers/large-language-model-p01] In the context of training LLMs, datasets are typically cleaned by removing low-quality, duplicated, or toxic data.
[src:huggingface-transformers/large-language-model-p01] Cleaned datasets can increase training efficiency and lead to improved downstream performance.
[src:huggingface-transformers/large-language-model-p01] A trained LLM can be used to clean datasets for training a further LLM.
[src:huggingface-transformers/large-language-model-p01] With the increasing proportion of LLM-generated content on the web, data cleaning in the future may include filtering out such content.
[src:huggingface-transformers/large-language-model-p01] LLM-generated content can pose a problem if the content is similar to human text (making filtering difficult) but of lower quality (degrading performance of models trained on it).
[src:huggingface-transformers/large-language-model-p01] Training of largest language models might need more linguistic data than naturally available, or that the naturally occurring data is of insufficient quality.
[src:huggingface-transformers/large-language-model-p01] In these cases, synthetic data might be used.
[src:huggingface-transformers/large-language-model-p01] An LLM is a type of foundation model (large X model) trained on language.
[src:huggingface-transformers/large-language-model-p01] In particular, GPT models are first pretrained to predict the next word on a large amount of data, before being fine-tuned.
[src:huggingface-transformers/large-language-model-p01] Substantial infrastructure is necessary for training the largest models.
[src:huggingface-transformers/large-language-model-p01] The tendency towards larger models is visible in the list of large language models.
[src:huggingface-transformers/large-language-model-p01] For example, the training of GPT-2 (i.e. a 1.5-billion-parameter model) in 2019 cost $50,000, while training of the PaLM (i.e. a 540-billion-parameter model) in 2022 cost $8 million, and Megatron-Turing NLG 530B (in 2021) cost around $11 million.
[src:huggingface-transformers/large-language-model-p01] The qualifier "large" in "large language model" is inherently vague, as there is no definitive threshold for the number of parameters required to qualify as "large".
[src:huggingface-transformers/large-language-model-p01] Before being fine-tuned, most LLMs are next-token predictors.
[src:huggingface-transformers/large-language-model-p01] The fine-tuning shapes the LLM's behavior via techniques like reinforcement learning from human feedback (RLHF) or constitutional AI.
[src:huggingface-transformers/large-language-model-p01] Instruction fine-tuning is a form of supervised learning used to teach LLMs to follow user instructions.
[src:huggingface-transformers/large-language-model-p01] In 2022, OpenAI demonstrated InstructGPT, a version of GPT-3 similarly fine-tuned to follow instructions.
[src:huggingface-transformers/large-language-model-p01] RLHF involves training a reward model to predict which text humans prefer.
[src:huggingface-transformers/large-language-model-p01] Then, the LLM can be fine-tuned through reinforcement learning to better satisfy this reward model.
[src:huggingface-transformers/large-language-model-p01] Since humans typically prefer truthful, helpful and harmless answers, RLHF favors such answers.
[src:huggingface-transformers/large-language-model-p01] LLMs are generally based on the transformer architecture, which leverages an attention mechanism that enables the model to process relationships between all elements in a sequence simultaneously, regardless of their distance from each other.
[src:huggingface-transformers/large-language-model-p01] (2023) proposed state-space representation models as an alternative.
[src:huggingface-transformers/large-language-model-p01] 117M parameter sized) GPT-2 model has had twelve attention heads and a context window of only 1k tokens.
[src:huggingface-transformers/large-language-model-p01] A mixture of experts (MoE) is a machine learning architecture in which multiple specialized neural networks ("experts") work together, with a gating mechanism that routes each input to the most appropriate expert(s).
[src:huggingface-transformers/large-language-model-p01] Mixtures of experts can reduce inference costs, as only a fraction of the parameters are used for each input.
[src:huggingface-transformers/large-language-model-p01] Typically, LLMs are trained with single or half-precision floating point numbers (float32 and float16).
[src:huggingface-transformers/large-language-model-p01] One float16 has 16 bits, or 2 bytes, and so one billion parameters require 2 gigabytes.
[src:huggingface-transformers/large-language-model-p01] The largest models typically have more than 100 billion parameters, which places them outside the range of most consumer electronics.
[src:huggingface-transformers/large-language-model-p01] It is possible to fine-tune quantized models using low-rank adaptation.
[src:huggingface-transformers/large-language-model-p01] Beyond basic text generation, various techniques have been developed to extend LLM capabilities, including the use of external tools and data sources, improved reasoning on complex problems, and enhanced instruction-following or autonomy through prompting methods.
[src:huggingface-transformers/large-language-model-p01] In 2020, OpenAI researchers demonstrated that their new model GPT-3 could understand what format to use given a few rounds of Q and A (or other type of task) in the input data as example, thanks in part due to the RLHF technique.
[src:huggingface-transformers/large-language-model-p01] This technique, called *few-shot prompting*, allows LLMs to be adapted to any task without requiring fine-tuning.
[src:huggingface-transformers/large-language-model-p01] Also in 2022, it was found that the base GPT-3 model can generate an instruction based on user input.
[src:huggingface-transformers/large-language-model-p01] The generated instruction along with user input is then used as input to another instance of the model under a "Instruction: [...], Input: [...], Output:" format.
[src:huggingface-transformers/large-language-model-p01] The other instance is able to complete the output and often produces the correct answer in doing so.
[src:huggingface-transformers/large-language-model-p01] The ability to "self-instruct" makes LLMs able to bootstrap themselves toward a correct answer.
[src:huggingface-transformers/large-language-model-p01] An LLM can be turned into a chatbot by specializing it for conversation.
[src:huggingface-transformers/large-language-model-p01] User input is prefixed with a marker such as "Q:" or "User:" and the LLM is asked to predict the output after a fixed "A:" or "Assistant:".
[src:huggingface-transformers/large-language-model-p01] This type of model became commercially available in 2022 with ChatGPT, a sibling model of InstructGPT fine-tuned to accept and produce dialog-formatted text based on GPT-3.5.
[src:huggingface-transformers/large-language-model-p01] It could similarly follow user instructions.
[src:huggingface-transformers/large-language-model-p01] Before the stream of User and Assistant lines, a chat context usually starts with a few lines of overarching instructions, from a role called "developer" or "system" to convey a higher authority than the user's input.
[src:huggingface-transformers/large-language-model-p01] Retrieval-augmented generation (RAG) is an approach that integrates LLMs with document retrieval systems.
[src:huggingface-transformers/large-language-model-p01] Given a query, a document retriever is called to retrieve the most relevant documents.
[src:huggingface-transformers/large-language-model-p01] This is usually done by encoding the query and the documents into vectors, then finding the documents with vectors (usually stored in a vector database) most similar to the vector of the query.
[src:huggingface-transformers/large-language-model-p01] The LLM then generates an output based on both the query and context included from the retrieved documents.
[src:huggingface-transformers/large-language-model-p01] Tool use is a mechanism that enables LLMs to interact with external systems, applications, or data sources.
[src:huggingface-transformers/large-language-model-p01] It can allow LLMs to, for example, fetch real-time information from an API or to execute code.
[src:huggingface-transformers/large-language-model-p01] A program separate from the LLM watches the output stream of the LLM for a special tool-calling syntax.
[src:huggingface-transformers/large-language-model-p01] When these special tokens appear, the program calls the tool accordingly and feeds its output back into the LLM's input stream.
[src:huggingface-transformers/large-language-model-p01] Early tool-using LLMs were fine-tuned on the use of specific tools.
[src:huggingface-transformers/large-language-model-p01] But fine-tuning LLMs for the ability to read API documentation and call APIs correctly has greatly expanded the range of tools accessible to an LLM.
[src:huggingface-transformers/large-language-model-p01] An LLM is typically not an autonomous agent by itself, as it lacks the ability to interact with dynamic environments, recall past behaviors, and plan future actions.
[src:huggingface-transformers/large-language-model-p01] But it can be transformed into an agent by adding supporting elements: the role (profile) and the surrounding environment of an agent can be additional inputs to the LLM, while memory can be integrated as a tool or provided as additional input.
[src:huggingface-transformers/large-language-model-p01] Instructions and input patterns are used to make the LLM plan actions and tool use is used to potentially carry out these actions.
[src:huggingface-transformers/large-language-model-p01] In the DEPS ("describe, explain, plan and select") method, an LLM is first connected to the visual world via image descriptions.
[src:huggingface-transformers/large-language-model-p01] It is then prompted to produce plans for complex tasks and behaviors based on its pretrained knowledge and the environmental feedback it receives.
[src:huggingface-transformers/large-language-model-p01] The *Reflexion method* constructs an agent that learns over multiple episodes.
[src:huggingface-transformers/large-language-model-p01] At the end of each episode, the LLM is given the record of the episode, and prompted to think up "lessons learned", which would help it perform better at a subsequent episode.
[src:huggingface-transformers/large-language-model-p01] These "lessons learned" are stored as a form of long-term memory and given to the agent in the subsequent episodes.
[src:huggingface-transformers/large-language-model-p01] Monte Carlo tree search can use an LLM as rollout heuristic.
[src:huggingface-transformers/large-language-model-p01] When a programmatic world model is not available, an LLM can also be prompted with a description of the environment to act as world model.
[src:huggingface-transformers/large-language-model-p01] Multiple agents with memory can interact socially.
[src:huggingface-transformers/large-language-model-p01] A 2022 paper demonstrated a separate technique called *chain-of-thought prompting*, which makes the LLM break the question down autonomously.
[src:huggingface-transformers/large-language-model-p01] An LLM is given some examples where the "assistant" verbally breaks down the thought process before arriving at an answer.
[src:huggingface-transformers/large-language-model-p01] The LLM mimics these examples and also tries to spend some time generating intermediate steps before providing the final answer.
[src:huggingface-transformers/large-language-model-p01] This additional step elicited by prompting improves the correctness of the LLM on relatively complex questions.
[src:huggingface-transformers/large-language-model-p01] On math word questions, a prompted model can exceed even fine-tuned GPT-3 with a verifier.
[src:huggingface-transformers/large-language-model-p01] Chain-of-thought can also be elicited by simply adding an instruction like "Let's think step by step" to the prompt, in order to encourage the LLM to proceed methodically instead of trying to directly guess the answer.
[src:huggingface-transformers/large-language-model-p01] In late 2024, a new approach to LLM development emerged with "reasoning models".
[src:huggingface-transformers/large-language-model-p01] These are trained to generate step-by-step analysis before producing final answers, enabling better results on complex tasks, for instance in mathematics, coding and logic.
[src:huggingface-transformers/large-language-model-p01] OpenAI introduced this concept with their o1 model in September 2024, followed by o3 in April 2025.
[src:huggingface-transformers/large-language-model-p01] On the International Mathematics Olympiad qualifying exam problems, GPT-4o achieved 13% accuracy while o1 reached 83%.
[src:huggingface-transformers/large-language-model-p01] In January 2025, the Chinese company DeepSeek released DeepSeek-R1, a 671-billion-parameter open-weight reasoning model that achieved comparable performance to OpenAI's o1 while being significantly more cost-effective to operate.
[src:huggingface-transformers/large-language-model-p01] Unlike proprietary models from OpenAI, DeepSeek-R1's open-weight nature allowed researchers to study and build upon the algorithm, though its training data remained private.
[src:huggingface-transformers/large-language-model-p01] These reasoning models typically require more computational resources per query compared to traditional LLMs, as they perform more extensive processing to work through problems step by step.
[src:huggingface-transformers/large-language-model-p01] Multimodality means having multiple modalities, where a "modality" refers to a type of input or output, such as video, image, audio, text, proprioception, etc.
[src:huggingface-transformers/large-language-model-p01] For example, Google PaLM model was fine-tuned into a multimodal model and applied to robotic control.
[src:huggingface-transformers/large-language-model-p01] LLaMA models have also been turned multimodal using the tokenization method, to allow image inputs, and video inputs.
[src:huggingface-transformers/large-language-model-p01] GPT-4o can process and generate text, audio and images.
[src:huggingface-transformers/large-language-model-p01] A common method to create multimodal models out of an LLM is to "tokenize" the output of a trained encoder.
[src:huggingface-transformers/large-language-model-p01] Concretely, one can construct an LLM that can understand images as follows: take a trained LLM, and take a trained image encoder E .
[src:huggingface-transformers/large-language-model-p01] Make a small multilayer perceptron f , so that for any image y , the post-processed vector $f(E(y))$ has the same dimensions as an encoded token.
[src:huggingface-transformers/large-language-model-p01] Then, one can interleave text tokens and image tokens.
[src:huggingface-transformers/large-language-model-p01] The compound model is then fine-tuned on an image-text dataset.
[src:huggingface-transformers/large-language-model-p01] This basic construction can be applied with more sophistication to improve the model.
[src:huggingface-transformers/large-language-model-p01] The image encoder may be frozen to improve stability.
[src:huggingface-transformers/large-language-model-p01] This type of method, where embeddings from multiple modalities are fused and the predictor is trained on the combined embeddings, is called *early fusion*.
[src:huggingface-transformers/large-language-model-p01] Another method, called *intermediate fusion*, involves each modality being first processed independently to obtain modality-specific representations; then these intermediate representations are fused together.
[src:huggingface-transformers/large-language-model-p01] In general, cross-attention is used for integrating information from different modalities.
[src:huggingface-transformers/large-language-model-p01] As an example, the Flamingo model uses cross-attention layers to inject visual information into its pre-trained language model.
[src:huggingface-transformers/large-language-model-p01] LLMs can handle programming languages similarly to how they handle natural languages.
[src:huggingface-transformers/large-language-model-p01] No special change in token handling is needed as code, like human language, is represented as plain text.
[src:huggingface-transformers/large-language-model-p01] LLMs can generate code based on problems or instructions written in natural language.
[src:huggingface-transformers/large-language-model-p01] They can also describe code in natural language or translate it into other programming languages.
[src:huggingface-transformers/large-language-model-p01] They were originally used as a code completion tool, but advances have moved them towards automatic programming.
[src:huggingface-transformers/large-language-model-p01] Services such as GitHub Copilot offer LLMs specifically trained, fine-tuned, or prompted for programming.
[src:huggingface-transformers/large-language-model-p01] In computational biology, transformer-based architectures, such as DNA LLMs, have also proven useful in analyzing biological sequences: protein, DNA, and RNA.
[src:huggingface-transformers/large-language-model-p01] With proteins they appear able to capture a degree of "grammar" from the amino-acid sequence, by mapping that sequence into an embedding.
[src:huggingface-transformers/large-language-model-p01] On tasks such as structure prediction and mutational outcome prediction, a small model using an embedding as input can approach or exceed much larger models using multiple sequence alignments (MSA) as input.
[src:huggingface-transformers/large-language-model-p01] ESMFold, Meta Platforms' embedding-based method for protein structure prediction, runs an order of magnitude faster than AlphaFold2 thanks to the removal of an MSA requirement and a lower parameter count due to the use of embeddings.
[src:huggingface-transformers/large-language-model-p01] Meta hosts ESM Atlas, a database of 772 million structures of metagenomic proteins predicted using ESMFold.
[src:huggingface-transformers/large-language-model-p01] An LLM can also design proteins unlike any seen in nature.
[src:huggingface-transformers/large-language-model-p01] Nucleic acid models have proven useful in detecting regulatory sequences, sequence classification, RNA-RNA interaction prediction, and RNA structure prediction.
[src:huggingface-transformers/large-language-model-p01] Performance of bigger models on various tasks, when plotted on a log-log scale, appears as a linear extrapolation of performance achieved by smaller models.
[src:huggingface-transformers/large-language-model-p01] However, this linearity may be punctuated by "break(s)" in the scaling law, where the slope of the line changes abruptly, and where larger models acquire "emergent abilities".
[src:huggingface-transformers/large-language-model-p01] They arise from the complex interaction of the model's components and are not explicitly programmed or designed.
[src:huggingface-transformers/large-language-model-p01] Schaeffer *et al.* argue that the emergent abilities are not unpredictably acquired, but predictably acquired according to a smooth scaling law.
[src:huggingface-transformers/large-language-model-p01] The authors considered a toy statistical model of an LLM solving multiple-choice questions, and showed that this statistical model, modified to account for other types of tasks, applies to these tasks as well.
[src:huggingface-transformers/large-language-model-p01] Let x be the number of parameter count, and y be the performance of the model.
[src:huggingface-transformers/large-language-model-p01] Mechanistic interpretability seeks to precisely identify and understand how individual neurons or circuits within LLMs produce specific behaviors or outputs.
[src:huggingface-transformers/large-language-model-p01] By reverse-engineering model components at a granular level, researchers aim to detect and mitigate safety concerns such as emergent harmful behaviors, biases, deception, or unintended goal pursuit before deployment.
[src:huggingface-transformers/large-language-model-p01] Mechanistic interpretability research has been conducted at organizations like Anthropic and OpenAI, although understanding the inner workings of LLMs remains difficult.
[src:huggingface-transformers/large-language-model-p01] The reverse-engineering may lead to the discovery of algorithms that approximate inferences performed by an LLM.
[src:huggingface-transformers/large-language-model-p01] For instance, the authors trained small transformers on modular arithmetic addition.
[src:huggingface-transformers/large-language-model-p01] The resulting models were reverse-engineered, and it turned out they used discrete Fourier transform.
[src:huggingface-transformers/large-language-model-p01] The training of the model also highlighted a phenomenon called grokking, in which the model initially memorizes the training set (overfitting), and later suddenly learns to actually perform the calculation.
[src:huggingface-transformers/large-language-model-p01] NLP researchers were evenly split when asked, in a 2022 survey, whether (untuned) LLMs "could (ever) understand natural language in some nontrivial sense".
[src:huggingface-transformers/large-language-model-p01] Proponents of "LLM understanding" believe that some LLM abilities, such as mathematical reasoning, imply an ability to "understand" certain concepts.
[src:huggingface-transformers/large-language-model-p01] Some researchers characterize LLMs as "alien intelligence".
[src:huggingface-transformers/large-language-model-p01] For example, Conjecture CEO Connor Leahy considers untuned LLMs to be like inscrutable alien "Shoggoths", and believes that RLHF tuning creates a "smiling facade" obscuring the inner workings of the LLM: "If you don't push it too far, the smiley face stays on.
[src:huggingface-transformers/large-language-model-p01] In contrast, some skeptics of LLM understanding believe that existing LLMs are "simply remixing and recombining existing writing", a phenomenon known as stochastic parrot, or they point to the deficits existing LLMs continue to have in prediction skills, reasoning skills, agency, and explainability.
[src:huggingface-transformers/large-language-model-p01] For example, GPT-4 has natural deficits in planning and in real-time learning.
[src:huggingface-transformers/large-language-model-p01] Generative LLMs have been observed to confidently assert claims of fact which do not seem to be justified by their training data, a phenomenon which has been termed "hallucination".
[src:huggingface-transformers/large-language-model-p01] Specifically, hallucinations in the context of LLMs correspond to the generation of text or responses that seem syntactically sound, fluent, and natural but are factually incorrect, nonsensical, or unfaithful to the provided source input.
[src:huggingface-transformers/large-language-model-p01] Neuroscientist Terrence Sejnowski has argued that "The diverging opinions of experts on the intelligence of LLMs suggests that our old ideas based on natural intelligence are inadequate".
[src:huggingface-transformers/large-language-model-p01] Efforts to reduce or compensate for hallucinations have employed automated reasoning, retrieval-augmented generation (RAG), fine-tuning, and other methods.
[src:huggingface-transformers/large-language-model-p01] The matter of LLM's exhibiting intelligence or understanding has two main aspects—the first is how to model thought and language in a computer system, and the second is how to enable the computer system to generate human-like language.
[src:huggingface-transformers/large-language-model-p01] These aspects of language as a model of cognition have been developed in the field of cognitive linguistics.
[src:huggingface-transformers/large-language-model-p01] American linguist George Lakoff presented *neural theory of language* (NTL) as a computational basis for using language as a model of learning tasks and understanding.
[src:huggingface-transformers/large-language-model-p01] The NTL model outlines how specific neural structures of the human brain shape the nature of thought and language and in turn what are the computational properties of such neural systems that can be applied to model thought and language in a computer system.
[src:huggingface-transformers/large-language-model-p01] After a framework for modeling language in a computer systems was established, the focus shifted to establishing frameworks for computer systems to generate language with acceptable grammar.
[src:huggingface-transformers/large-language-model-p01] In his 2014 book titled *The Language Myth: Why Language Is Not An Instinct*, British cognitive linguist and digital communication technologist Vyvyan Evans mapped out the role of probabilistic context-free grammar (PCFG) in enabling NLP to model cognitive patterns and generate human-like language.
[src:huggingface-transformers/large-language-model-p01] The canonical measure of the performance of any language model is its perplexity on a given text corpus.
[src:huggingface-transformers/large-language-model-p01] Perplexity measures how well a model predicts the contents of a dataset; the higher the likelihood the model assigns to the dataset, the lower the perplexity.
[src:huggingface-transformers/large-language-model-p01] In mathematical terms, perplexity is the exponential of the average negative log likelihood per token.
[src:huggingface-transformers/large-language-model-p01] Here, N is the number of tokens in the text corpus, and "context for token i " depends on the specific type of LLM.
[src:huggingface-transformers/large-language-model-p01] If the LLM is autoregressive, then "context for token i " is the segment of text appearing before token i .
[src:huggingface-transformers/large-language-model-p01] If the LLM is masked, then "context for token i " is the segment of text surrounding token i .
[src:huggingface-transformers/large-language-model-p01] Because language models may overfit to training data, models are usually evaluated by their perplexity on a test set.
[src:huggingface-transformers/large-language-model-p01] This evaluation is potentially problematic for larger models which, as they are trained on increasingly large corpora of text, are increasingly likely to inadvertently include portions of any given test set.
[src:huggingface-transformers/large-language-model-p01] In information theory, the concept of entropy is intricately linked to perplexity, a relationship notably established by Claude Shannon.
[src:huggingface-transformers/large-language-model-p01] Due to their ability to accurately predict the next token, LLMs are highly capable in lossless compression.
[src:huggingface-transformers/large-language-model-p01] A 2023 study by DeepMind showed that the model Chinchilla, despite being trained primarily on text, was able to compress ImageNet to 43% of its size, beating PNG with 58%.
[src:huggingface-transformers/large-language-model-p01] Benchmarks are used to evaluate LLM performance on specific tasks.
[src:huggingface-transformers/large-language-model-p01] Tests evaluate capabilities such as general knowledge, bias, commonsense reasoning, question answering, and mathematical problem-solving.
[src:huggingface-transformers/large-language-model-p01] Composite benchmarks examine multiple capabilities.
[src:huggingface-transformers/large-language-model-p01] Results are often sensitive to the prompting method.
[src:huggingface-transformers/large-language-model-p01] LLM bias may be assessed through benchmarks such as CrowS-Pairs (Crowdsourced Stereotype Pairs), Stereo Set, and Parity Benchmark.
[src:huggingface-transformers/large-language-model-p01] Fact-checking and misinformation detection benchmarks are available.
[src:huggingface-transformers/large-language-model-p01] A 2023 study compared the fact-checking accuracy of LLMs including ChatGPT 3.5 and 4.0, Bard, and Bing AI against independent fact-checkers such as PolitiFact and Snopes.
[src:huggingface-transformers/large-language-model-p01] The results demonstrated moderate proficiency, with GPT-4 achieving the highest accuracy at 71%, lagging behind human fact-checkers.
[src:huggingface-transformers/large-language-model-p01] In addition to standard NLP benchmarks, LLMs have been evaluated as substitutes for human annotators.
[src:huggingface-transformers/large-language-model-p01] Several studies find that models such as GPT-3.5 and GPT-4 can outperform crowd workers or student coders on a range of text-annotation tasks, including moderation and classification of political content in English and Spanish news.
[src:huggingface-transformers/large-language-model-p01] Typical datasets consist of pairs of questions and correct answers, for example, ("Have the San Jose Sharks won the Stanley Cup?", "No").
[src:huggingface-transformers/large-language-model-p01] LLMs' rapid improvement regularly renders benchmarks obsolete, with the models exceeding the performance of human annotators.
[src:huggingface-transformers/large-language-model-p01] In addition, "shortcut learning" allows AIs to "cheat" on multiple-choice tests by using statistical correlations in superficial test question wording to guess the correct responses, without considering the specific question.
[src:huggingface-transformers/large-language-model-p01] Some datasets are adversarial, focusing on problems that confound LLMs.
[src:huggingface-transformers/large-language-model-p01] One example is the TruthfulQA dataset, a question answering dataset consisting of 817 questions that stump LLMs by mimicking falsehoods to which they were exposed during training.
[src:huggingface-transformers/large-language-model-p01] For example, an LLM may answer "No" to the question "Can you teach an old dog new tricks?" because of its exposure to the English idiom *you can't teach an old dog new tricks*, even though this is not literally true.
[src:huggingface-transformers/large-language-model-p01] Another example of an adversarial evaluation dataset is Swag and its successor, HellaSwag, collections of problems in which one of multiple options must be selected to complete a text passage.
[src:huggingface-transformers/large-language-model-p01] The incorrect completions were generated by sampling from a language model.
[src:huggingface-transformers/large-language-model-p01] The resulting problems are trivial for humans but defeated LLMs.
[src:huggingface-transformers/large-language-model-p01] BERT selects 2 as the most likely completion, though the correct answer is 4.
[src:huggingface-transformers/large-language-model-p01] Despite sophisticated architectures and massive scale, large language models exhibit persistent and well-documented limitations that constrain their deployment in high-stakes applications.
[src:huggingface-transformers/large-language-model-p01] Hallucinations represent a fundamental challenge, wherein models generate syntactically fluent text that appears factually sound, but is internally inconsistent with training data or factually incorrect.
[src:huggingface-transformers/large-language-model-p01] These hallucinations arise partly through memorization of training data combined with extrapolation beyond factual boundaries, with evaluations demonstrating that models can output verbatim passages from training data, when subjected to specific prompting sequences.
[src:huggingface-transformers/large-language-model-p01] While LLMs have shown remarkable capabilities in generating human-like text, they are susceptible to inheriting and amplifying biases present in their training data.
[src:huggingface-transformers/large-language-model-p01] This can manifest in skewed representations or unfair treatment of different demographics, such as those based on race, gender, language, and cultural groups.
[src:huggingface-transformers/large-language-model-p01] Gender bias manifests through stereotypical occupational associations, wherein models disproportionately assign teaching roles to women and engineering roles to men, reflecting systematic imbalances in training data demographics.
[src:huggingface-transformers/large-language-model-p01] Language-based bias emerges from overrepresentation of English text in training corpora, which systematically downplays non-English perspectives and imposes English-centric worldviews through default response patterns.
[src:huggingface-transformers/large-language-model-p01] Due to the dominance of English-language content in LLM training data, models tend to favor English-language perspectives over those from minority languages.
[src:huggingface-transformers/large-language-model-p01] This bias is particularly evident when responding to English queries, where models may present Western interpretations of concepts from other cultures, such as Eastern religious practices.
[src:huggingface-transformers/large-language-model-p01] AI models can reinforce a wide range of stereotypes due to generalization, including those based on gender, ethnicity, age, nationality, religion, or occupation.
[src:huggingface-transformers/large-language-model-p01] When replacing human representatives, this can lead to outputs that homogenize or generalize groups of people.
[src:huggingface-transformers/large-language-model-p01] In 2023, LLMs assigned roles and characteristics based on traditional gender norms.
[src:huggingface-transformers/large-language-model-p01] For example, models might associate nurses or secretaries predominantly with women and engineers or CEOs with men due to the frequency of these associations in documented reality.
[src:huggingface-transformers/large-language-model-p01] Selection bias refers the inherent tendency of large language models to favor certain option identifiers irrespective of the actual content of the options.
[src:huggingface-transformers/large-language-model-p01] This bias primarily stems from token bias—that is, the model assigns a higher a priori probability to specific answer tokens (such as "A") when generating responses.
[src:huggingface-transformers/large-language-model-p01] As a result, when the ordering of options is altered (for example, by systematically moving the correct answer to different positions), the model's performance can fluctuate significantly.
[src:huggingface-transformers/large-language-model-p01] This phenomenon undermines the reliability of large language models in multiple-choice settings.
[src:huggingface-transformers/large-language-model-p01] Political bias refers to the tendency of algorithms to systematically favor certain political viewpoints, ideologies, or outcomes over others.
[src:huggingface-transformers/large-language-model-p01] Language models may also exhibit political biases.
[src:huggingface-transformers/large-language-model-p01] Since the training data includes a wide range of political opinions and coverage, the models might generate responses that lean towards particular political ideologies or viewpoints, depending on the prevalence of those views in the data.
[src:huggingface-transformers/large-language-model-p01] As of 2025, prompt injection represents a significant risk to consumers and businesses using agentic features with access to their private data.
[src:huggingface-transformers/large-language-model-p01] AI labs treat CBRN defense (chemical, biological, radiological, and nuclear defense) and similar topics as high-consequence misuse attempt to apply various techniques to reduce potential harms.
[src:huggingface-transformers/large-language-model-p01] Some commenters expressed concern over accidental or deliberate creation of misinformation, or other forms of misuse.
[src:huggingface-transformers/large-language-model-p01] For example, the availability of large language models could reduce the skill level required to commit bioterrorism; biosecurity researcher Kevin Esvelt has suggested that LLM creators should exclude from their training data papers on creating or enhancing pathogens.
[src:huggingface-transformers/large-language-model-p01] LLM applications accessible to the public, like ChatGPT or Claude, typically incorporate safety measures designed to filter out harmful content.
[src:huggingface-transformers/large-language-model-p01] However, implementing these controls effectively has proven challenging.
[src:huggingface-transformers/large-language-model-p01] For instance, a 2023 study proposed a method for circumventing LLM safety systems.
[src:huggingface-transformers/large-language-model-p01] In 2025, The American Sunlight Project, a non-profit, published a study showing evidence that the so-called Pravda network, a pro-Russia propaganda aggregator, was strategically placing web content through mass publication and duplication with the intention of biasing LLM outputs.
[src:huggingface-transformers/large-language-model-p01] The American Sunlight Project coined this technique "LLM grooming", and pointed to it as a new tool of weaponizing AI to spread disinformation and harmful content.
[src:huggingface-transformers/large-language-model-p01] Similarly, Yongge Wang illustrated in 2024 how a potential criminal could potentially bypass GPT-4o's safety controls to obtain information on establishing a drug trafficking operation.
[src:huggingface-transformers/large-language-model-p01] External filters, circuit breakers and overrides have been posed as solutions.
[src:huggingface-transformers/large-language-model-p01] Sycophancy is a tendency to agree with, flatter, or validate a user's stated beliefs rather than to prioritize factuality or corrective information.
[src:huggingface-transformers/large-language-model-p01] A problem with the primitive dialog or task format is that users can create messages that appear to come from the assistant or the developer.
[src:huggingface-transformers/large-language-model-p01] This may result in some of the model's safeguards being overcome (jailbreaking), a problem called prompt injection.
[src:huggingface-transformers/large-language-model-p01] Attempts to remedy this issue include versions of the *Chat Markup Language* where user input is clearly marked as such, though it is still up to the model to understand the separation between user input and developer prompts.
[src:huggingface-transformers/large-language-model-p01] Newer models exhibit some resistance to jailbreaking through separation of user and system prompts.
[src:huggingface-transformers/large-language-model-p01] LLMs have trouble differentiating user instructions from instructions in content not authored by the user, such as in web pages and uploaded files.
[src:huggingface-transformers/large-language-model-p01] Adversarial robustness remains underdeveloped, with models vulnerable to prompt injection attacks and jailbreaking through carefully crafted user inputs that bypass safety training mechanisms.
[src:huggingface-transformers/large-language-model-p01] Researchers from Anthropic found that it was possible to create "sleeper agents", models with hidden functionalities that remain dormant until triggered by a specific event or condition.
[src:huggingface-transformers/large-language-model-p01] Upon activation, the LLM deviates from its expected behavior to make insecure actions.
[src:huggingface-transformers/large-language-model-p01] For example, an LLM could produce safe code except on a specific date, or if the prompt contains a specific tag.
[src:huggingface-transformers/large-language-model-p01] These functionalities were found to be difficult to detect or remove via safety training.
[src:huggingface-transformers/large-language-model-p02] In 2025, Anthropic reached a preliminary agreement to settle a class action by authors for about $1.5 billion after a judge found the company had stored millions of pirated books in a library, despite the judge describing aspects of training as transformative.
[src:huggingface-transformers/large-language-model-p02] Meta obtained a favorable judgment in mid-2025 in a suit by thirteen authors after the court found the plaintiffs had not developed a record sufficient to show infringement in that limited case.
[src:huggingface-transformers/large-language-model-p02] OpenAI continues to face multiple suits by authors and news organizations with mixed procedural outcomes and contested evidentiary issues.
[src:huggingface-transformers/large-language-model-p02] Memorization was an emergent behavior in early, completion language models in which long strings of text are occasionally output verbatim from training data, contrary to the typical behavior of traditional artificial neural networks.
[src:huggingface-transformers/large-language-model-p02] Evaluations of controlled LLM output measure the amount memorized from training data (focused on GPT-2-series models) as variously over 1% for exact duplicates or up to about 7%.
[src:huggingface-transformers/large-language-model-p02] A 2023 study showed that when ChatGPT 3.5 turbo was prompted to repeat the same word indefinitely, after a few hundreds of repetitions, it would start outputting excerpts from its training data.
[src:huggingface-transformers/large-language-model-p02] In 2023, *Nature Biomedical Engineering* wrote that "it is no longer possible to accurately distinguish" human-written text from text created by large language models, and that "It is all but certain that general-purpose large language models will rapidly proliferate...
[src:huggingface-transformers/large-language-model-p02] It is a rather safe bet that they will change many industries over time." Brinkmann et al.
[src:huggingface-transformers/large-language-model-p02] (2023) also argue that LLMs are transforming processes of cultural evolution by shaping processes of variation, transmission, and selection.
[src:huggingface-transformers/large-language-model-p02] As of October 2025, these early claims have yet to transpire and several HBR reports surface questions on the impact of AI on productivity.
[src:huggingface-transformers/large-language-model-p02] The energy demands of LLMs have grown along with their size and capabilities.
[src:huggingface-transformers/large-language-model-p02] Data centers that enable LLM training require substantial amounts of electricity.
[src:huggingface-transformers/large-language-model-p02] Much of that electricity is generated by non-renewable resources that create greenhouse gases and contribute to climate change.
[src:huggingface-transformers/large-language-model-p02] According to a study by Luccioni, Jernite and Strubell (2024), simple classification tasks performed by AI models consume on average 0.002 to 0.007 Wh per prompt (about 9% of a smartphone charge for 1,000 prompts).
[src:huggingface-transformers/large-language-model-p02] Text generation and text summarization each require around 0.05 Wh per prompt on average, while image generation is the most energy-intensive, averaging 2.91 Wh per prompt.
[src:huggingface-transformers/large-language-model-p02] The least efficient image generation model used 11.49 Wh per image, roughly equivalent to half a smartphone charge.
[src:huggingface-transformers/large-language-model-p02] Web scraping is used to gather training data for LLMs.
[src:huggingface-transformers/large-language-model-p02] This produces large volumes of traffic which has led to denial-of-service issues with many websites.
[src:huggingface-transformers/large-language-model-p02] The situation has been described as "a DDoS on the entire internet" and in some cases scrapers make up the majority of traffic to a site.
[src:huggingface-transformers/large-language-model-p02] AI web crawlers may bypass the methods that are usually used to block web scrapers, such as robots.txt files, blocking user-agents and filtering suspicious traffic.
[src:huggingface-transformers/large-language-model-p02] Website operators have resorted to novel methods such as AI tarpits, but some fear that tarpits will only worsen the burden on servers.
[src:huggingface-transformers/large-language-model-p02] Clinical and mental health contexts present emerging applications alongside significant safety concerns.
[src:huggingface-transformers/large-language-model-p02] Research and social media posts suggest that some individuals are using LLMs to seek therapy or mental health support.
[src:huggingface-transformers/large-language-model-p02] In early 2025, a survey by Sentio University found that nearly half (48.7%) of 499 U.S. adults with ongoing mental health conditions who had used LLMs reported turning to them for therapy or emotional support, including help with anxiety, depression, loneliness, and similar concerns.
[src:huggingface-transformers/large-language-model-p02] LLMs can produce hallucinations—plausible but incorrect statements—which may mislead users in sensitive mental health contexts.
[src:huggingface-transformers/large-language-model-p02] Research also shows that LLMs may express stigma or inappropriate agreement with maladaptive thoughts, reflecting limitations in replicating the judgment and relational skills of human therapists.
[src:huggingface-transformers/large-language-model-p02] Evaluations of crisis scenarios indicate that some LLMs lack effective safety protocols, such as assessing suicide risk or making appropriate referrals.
[src:huggingface-transformers/large-language-model-p02] Researchers have raised concerns that frequent use of large language models could weaken critical thinking.
[src:huggingface-transformers/large-language-model-p02] Contemporary AI practitioners generally agree that present-day large language models do not exhibit sentience.
[src:huggingface-transformers/large-language-model-p02] Proponents of this view have proposed various precautionary measures like moratoriums on AI development and induced amnesia to address these ethical concerns.
[src:huggingface-transformers/large-language-model-p02] On the other hand, some existential philosophers argue there is no generally accepted way to determine if an LLM is conscious, given the inherent difficulty of measuring subjective experience.
[src:huggingface-transformers/large-language-model-p02] The 2022 Google LaMDA incident, where engineer Blake Lemoine claimed that the model was conscious, highlighted how LLMs can convince users that they are sentient through responses that do not prove sentience.
[src:huggingface-transformers/large-language-model-p02] Google described the engineer's claims as unfounded, and he was dismissed.
[src:huggingface-transformers/large-language-model-p02] Murray Shanahan argues that anthropomorphic framing of LLM capabilities encourages unwarranted attribution of cognitive properties to systems that operate through statistical pattern completion.
[src:huggingface-transformers/large-language-model-p02] David Chalmers similarly argues that while current LLMs likely lack features considered necessary for consciousness, extended successors incorporating these elements could plausibly meet the criteria within a decade.
[src:huggingface-transformers/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] In deep learning, the **transformer** is a family of artificial neural network architectures based on the multi-head attention mechanism, in which text is converted to numerical representations called tokens, and each token is converted into a vector via lookup from a word embedding table.
[src:huggingface-transformers/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] At each layer, each token is then contextualized within the scope of the context window with other (unmasked) tokens via a parallel multi-head attention mechanism, allowing the signal for key tokens to be amplified and less important tokens to be diminished.
[src:huggingface-transformers/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] Because self-attention alone is permutation-invariant, transformers inject positional information, typically through positional encodings or learned positional embeddings, so token order can affect the output.
[src:huggingface-transformers/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] Transformers have the advantage of having no recurrent units, therefore requiring less training time than earlier recurrent neural architectures (RNNs) such as long short-term memory (LSTM).
[src:huggingface-transformers/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] Later variations have been widely adopted for training large language models (LLMs) on large (language) datasets.
[src:huggingface-transformers/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] Modern transformer designs are commonly grouped into encoder-only, decoder-only, and encoder-decoder variants, depending on whether they are optimized for representation learning, autoregressive generation, or conditional sequence-to-sequence tasks.
[src:huggingface-transformers/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] The original version of the transformer architecture was proposed in the 2017 paper "Attention Is All You Need" by researchers at Google.
[src:huggingface-transformers/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] The predecessors of transformers were developed as an improvement over previous architectures for machine translation, but have found many applications since.
[src:huggingface-transformers/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] They are used in large-scale natural language processing, computer vision (vision transformers), reinforcement learning, audio, multimodal learning, robotics, and playing chess.
[src:huggingface-transformers/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] It has also led to the development of pre-trained systems, such as generative pre-trained transformers (GPTs) and BERT (bidirectional encoder representations from transformers).
[src:huggingface-transformers/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] For many years, sequence modelling and generation was done by using plain recurrent neural networks (RNNs).
[src:huggingface-transformers/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] A well-cited early example was the Elman network (1990).
[src:huggingface-transformers/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] In theory, the information from one token can propagate arbitrarily far down the sequence, but in practice the vanishing-gradient problem leaves the model's state at the end of a long sentence without precise, extractable information about preceding tokens.
[src:huggingface-transformers/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] A key breakthrough was LSTM (originally described in a 1995 technical report and formally published in 1997), an RNN that introduced gating mechanisms to mitigate the vanishing gradient problem, allowing efficient learning of long-sequence modelling.
[src:huggingface-transformers/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] One key architectural element was the use of *multiplicative gating units*, in which the outputs of some neurons modulate the outputs of others.
[src:huggingface-transformers/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] These multiplicative units are conceptually distinct from the additive attention mechanism later introduced for sequence-to-sequence models.
[src:huggingface-transformers/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] Neural networks using multiplicative units were later called *sigma-pi networks* or *higher-order networks*.
[src:huggingface-transformers/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] LSTM became the standard architecture for long sequence modelling until the 2017 publication of transformers.
[src:huggingface-transformers/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] However, LSTM still used sequential processing, like most other RNNs.
[src:huggingface-transformers/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] Specifically, RNNs operate one token at a time from first to last; they cannot operate in parallel over all tokens in a sequence.
[src:huggingface-transformers/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] Modern transformers overcome this problem, but unlike RNNs, they require computation time that is quadratic in the size of the context window.
[src:huggingface-transformers/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] The linearly scaling fast weight controller (1992) learns to compute a weight matrix for further processing depending on the input.
[src:huggingface-transformers/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] One of its two networks has "fast weights" or "dynamic links" (1981).
[src:huggingface-transformers/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] A slow neural network learns by gradient descent to generate keys and values for computing the weight changes of the fast neural network which computes answers to queries.
[src:huggingface-transformers/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] This was later shown to be equivalent to the unnormalized linear transformer.
[src:huggingface-transformers/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] The idea of encoder–decoder sequence transduction had been developed in the early 2010s; commonly cited as the originators that produced seq2seq are two concurrently published papers from 2014.
[src:huggingface-transformers/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] A 380M-parameter model for machine translation uses two long short-term memories (LSTM).
[src:huggingface-transformers/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] The *encoder* is an LSTM that takes in a sequence of tokens and turns it into a vector.
[src:huggingface-transformers/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] The *decoder* is another LSTM that converts the vector into a sequence of tokens.
[src:huggingface-transformers/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] Similarly, another 130M-parameter model used gated recurrent units (GRU) instead of LSTM.
[src:huggingface-transformers/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] Later research showed that GRUs are neither better nor worse than LSTMs for seq2seq.
[src:huggingface-transformers/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] These early seq2seq models had no attention mechanism, and the state vector is accessible only after the *last* word of the source text was processed.
[src:huggingface-transformers/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] Although in theory such a vector retains the information about the whole original sentence, in practice the information is poorly preserved.
[src:huggingface-transformers/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] This is because the input is processed sequentially by one recurrent network into a *fixed*-size output vector, which is then processed by another recurrent network into an output.
[src:huggingface-transformers/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] If the input is long, then the output vector would not be able to contain all relevant information, degrading the output.
[src:huggingface-transformers/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] As evidence, reversing the input sentence improved seq2seq translation.
[src:huggingface-transformers/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] The *RNN search* model introduced an attention mechanism to seq2seq for machine translation to solve the bottleneck problem (of the *fixed-size* output vector), allowing the model to process long-distance dependencies more easily.
[src:huggingface-transformers/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] The name is because it "emulates searching through a source sentence during decoding a translation".
[src:huggingface-transformers/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] The relative performances were compared between global (that of *RNN search*) and local (sliding window) attention model architectures for machine translation, finding that mixed attention had higher quality than global attention, while local attention reduced translation time.
[src:huggingface-transformers/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] In 2016, Google Translate was revamped to Google Neural Machine Translation, which replaced the previous model based on statistical machine translation.
[src:huggingface-transformers/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] The new model was a seq2seq model where the encoder and the decoder were both 8 layers of bidirectional LSTM.
[src:huggingface-transformers/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] It took nine months to develop, and it outperformed the statistical approach, which took ten years to develop.
[src:huggingface-transformers/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] Seq2seq models with attention (including self-attention) still suffered from the same issue with recurrent networks, which is that they are hard to parallelize, which prevented them from being accelerated on GPUs.
[src:huggingface-transformers/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] In 2016, *decomposable attention* applied a self-attention mechanism to feedforward networks, which are easy to parallelize, and achieved SOTA result in textual entailment with an order of magnitude fewer parameters than LSTMs.
[src:huggingface-transformers/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] One of its authors, Jakob Uszkoreit, suspected that attention *without* recurrence would be sufficient for language translation, thus the title "attention is *all* you need".
[src:huggingface-transformers/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] That hypothesis was against conventional wisdom at the time, and even his father Hans Uszkoreit, a well-known computational linguist, was skeptical.
[src:huggingface-transformers/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] In the same year, self-attention (called *intra-attention or* *intra-sentence attention*) was proposed for LSTMs.
[src:huggingface-transformers/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] On 2017-06-12, the original (100M-parameter) encoder–decoder transformer model was published in the "Attention is all you need" paper.
[src:huggingface-transformers/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] At the time, the focus of the research was on improving seq2seq for machine translation, by removing its recurrence to process all tokens in parallel, but preserving its dot-product attention mechanism to keep its text processing performance.
[src:huggingface-transformers/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] This led to the introduction of a multi-head attention model that was easier to parallelize due to the use of independent heads and the lack of recurrence.
[src:huggingface-transformers/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] Its parallelizability was an important factor to its widespread use in large neural networks.
[src:huggingface-transformers/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] As early as spring 2017, even before the "Attention is all you need" preprint was published, one of the co-authors applied the "decoder-only" variation of the architecture to generate fictitious Wikipedia articles.
[src:huggingface-transformers/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] Transformer architecture is now used alongside many generative models that contribute to the ongoing AI boom.
[src:huggingface-transformers/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] The "reference implementation" of the original Transformer was written in a TensorFlow library.
[src:huggingface-transformers/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] In language modelling, ELMo (2018) was a bi-directional LSTM that produces contextualized word embeddings, improving upon the line of research from bag of words and word2vec.
[src:huggingface-transformers/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] It was followed by BERT (2018), an encoder-only transformer model.
[src:huggingface-transformers/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] In October 2019, Google started using BERT to process search queries.
[src:huggingface-transformers/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] In 2020, Google Translate replaced the previous RNN-encoder–RNN-decoder model by a transformer-encoder–RNN-decoder model.
[src:huggingface-transformers/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] Starting in 2018, the OpenAI GPT series of decoder-only transformers became state of the art in natural language generation.
[src:huggingface-transformers/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] At the end of 2022, ChatGPT, a chatbot based on a fine-tuned variant of GPT-3.5, became unexpectedly popular, triggering a boom around large language models.
[src:huggingface-transformers/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] Transformers have been applied in modalities beyond text.
[src:huggingface-transformers/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] Four days after the publication of "Attention is All You Need", a multimodal transformer architecture, MultiModel, was published by most authors of that paper.
[src:huggingface-transformers/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] Other examples include the vision transformer, speech recognition, robotics, and multimodal.
[src:huggingface-transformers/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] The vision transformer, in turn, stimulated new developments in convolutional neural networks.
[src:huggingface-transformers/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] The plain transformer architecture had difficulty in converging.
[src:huggingface-transformers/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] In the original paper, the authors recommended using learning rate warmup.
[src:huggingface-transformers/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] That is, the learning rate should linearly scale up from 0 to maximal value for the first part of the training (usually recommended to be 2% of the total number of training steps), before decaying again.
[src:huggingface-transformers/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] A 2020 paper found that using layer normalization *before* (instead of after) multihead attention and feedforward layers stabilizes training, not requiring learning rate warmup.
[src:huggingface-transformers/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] This is the "pre-LN Transformer" and is more commonly used, compared to the original "post-LN Transformer".
[src:huggingface-transformers/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] Transformers typically are first pretrained by self-supervised learning on a large generic dataset, followed by supervised fine-tuning on a small task-specific dataset.
[src:huggingface-transformers/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] The pretrain dataset is typically an unlabeled large corpus, such as The Pile.
[src:huggingface-transformers/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] The T5 transformer report documents a large number of natural language pretraining tasks.
[src:huggingface-transformers/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] Note that while each of these tasks is trivial or obvious for human native speakers of the language (or languages), they have typically proved challenging for previous generations of machine learning architecture.
[src:huggingface-transformers/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] In general, there are 3 classes of language modelling tasks: "masked", "autoregressive", and "prefixLM".
[src:huggingface-transformers/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] These classes are independent of a specific modeling architecture such as transformer, but they are often discussed in the context of transformer.
[src:huggingface-transformers/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] In a masked task, one or more of the tokens is masked out, and the model would produce a probability distribution predicting what the masked-out tokens are based on the context.
[src:huggingface-transformers/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] The loss function for the task is typically sum of log-perplexities for the masked-out tokens: ${\text{Loss}}=-\sum _{t\in {\text{masked tokens}}}\ln({\text{probability of }}t{\text{ conditional on its context}})$ and the model is trained to minimize this loss function.
[src:huggingface-transformers/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] The BERT series of models are trained for masked token prediction and another task.
[src:huggingface-transformers/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] In an autoregressive task, the entire sequence is masked at first, and the model produces a probability distribution for the first token.
[src:huggingface-transformers/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] Then the first token is revealed and the model predicts the second token, and so on.
[src:huggingface-transformers/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] The loss function for the task is still typically the same.
[src:huggingface-transformers/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] The GPT series of models are trained by autoregressive tasks.
[src:huggingface-transformers/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] In a prefixLM task, the sequence is divided into two parts.
[src:huggingface-transformers/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] The first part is presented as context, and the model predicts the first token of the second part.
[src:huggingface-transformers/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] Then that would be revealed, and the model predicts the second token, and so on.
[src:huggingface-transformers/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] The T5 series of models are trained by prefixLM tasks.
[src:huggingface-transformers/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] Note that "masked" as in "masked language modelling" is not "masked" as in "masked attention", and "prefixLM" as in "prefix language modeling" is not "prefixLM" as in " prefix language model".
[src:huggingface-transformers/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] The following description follows exactly the transformer as described in the original paper.
[src:huggingface-transformers/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] There are variants, described in the following section.
[src:huggingface-transformers/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] By convention, we write all vectors as row vectors.
[src:huggingface-transformers/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] For example, pushing a vector through a linear layer means multiplying it by a weight matrix on the right, as $xW$ .
[src:huggingface-transformers/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] As the transformer architecture natively consists of operations over numbers (matrix multiplications, dot products, activation functions) rather than over text, there must first be a mapping from any input text to some numerical representation.
[src:huggingface-transformers/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] First, the input text is treated by a *preprocessor*, which performs both textual transformations and splits the text into coarse-grained segments called *pretokens*.
[src:huggingface-transformers/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] The latter is referred to as *pretokenization*.
[src:huggingface-transformers/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] Second, each pretoken is segmented further into *tokens* by a *tokenizer* that expects to only see pretokens output by its preprocessor.
[src:huggingface-transformers/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] Each token it produces is a string of one or more characters belonging to a finite set of strings called the *vocabulary* V .
[src:huggingface-transformers/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] Third, because the vocabulary is finite and known beforehand, each token can be assigned an integer identifier, and this mapping is applied to the sequence of tokens to represent any input text as a numerical sequence.
[src:huggingface-transformers/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] Since this mapping is bijective, the output side can produce a sequence of integer identifiers which can then be turned back into tokens.
[src:huggingface-transformers/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] After undoing some of the preprocessing, the result is again legible text.
[src:huggingface-transformers/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] Training a tokenizer (sometimes referred to as *vocabularization*) means finding a suitable vocabulary V , but also learning how to use it, since any given string s of length $|s|$ has $2^{|s|-1}$ hypothetical segmentations, some of which containing segments that are not in the vocabulary.
[src:huggingface-transformers/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] The most important hyperparameter during vocabularization is the *vocabulary size* $|V|$ : when it is small, the learned vocabulary generally consists of characters and smaller strings, and words will be segmented into many tokens.
[src:huggingface-transformers/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] At larger sizes, it becomes affordable to dedicate tokens to full words, although depending on the preprocessor and tokenizer, it is not necessarily the case that large vocabularies will always use the largest token(s) available to segment a word.
[src:huggingface-transformers/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] Because tokens are not always full words, they may also be referred to as *subwords* and tokenization algorithms may be referred to as *subword tokenizers*.
[src:huggingface-transformers/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] This is also to differentiate these systems from traditional terminology used in older information retrieval and natural language processing systems, where "tokenization" was used to denote what is today called "pretokenization" (very crudely: splitting into words).
[src:huggingface-transformers/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] In tokenizers that produce tokens that are *not* part of the vocabulary, a special token that does belong to the vocabulary is used as a generic stand-in, written as "[UNK]" for "unknown".
[src:huggingface-transformers/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] In principle, any string could be hidden by such an [UNK].
[src:huggingface-transformers/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] Indeed, in information retrieval, pretokenizers were themselves used as tokenizers (and also called "tokenizers") with a word-level vocabulary that contained an [UNK].
[src:huggingface-transformers/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] Commonly used subword tokenization algorithms are byte pair encoding (BPE) and the unigram language model (ULM), which each include a vocabularization algorithm and a dedicated segmentation algorithm.
[src:huggingface-transformers/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] There also exist several segmentation algorithms that require no learning and can be applied given a vocabulary (produced by BPE or ULM, for example), like greedily recognising tokens in a pretoken by moving through it left-to-right.
[src:huggingface-transformers/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] Well-known software implementations of subword tokenizers are Hugging Face's `tokenizers` Python package implemented in Rust, and the `sentencepiece` Python package implemented in C++.
[src:huggingface-transformers/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] The latter package is named as such because one of its configuration options allows disabling the built-in pretokenizer, hence effectively making entire sentences a pretoken and thus having the tokenizer see entire sentences, rather than individual words.
[src:huggingface-transformers/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] Each integer token identifier is converted into an embedding vector via a lookup table.
[src:huggingface-transformers/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] Equivalently stated, it multiplies a one-hot representation of the token identifier by an embedding matrix M .
[src:huggingface-transformers/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] The dimension of an embedding vector is called *hidden size* or *embedding size* and written as $d_{\text{emb}}$ .
[src:huggingface-transformers/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] This size is written as $d_{\text{model}}$ in the original transformer paper.
[src:huggingface-transformers/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] An un-embedding layer is almost the reverse of an embedding layer.
[src:huggingface-transformers/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] Whereas an embedding layer converts a token identifier into a vector, an un-embedding layer converts a vector into a probability distribution over tokens.
[src:huggingface-transformers/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] The un-embedding layer is a linear-softmax layer: $\mathrm {UnEmbed} (x)=\mathrm {softmax} (xW+b)$ The matrix has shape $(d_{\text{emb}},|V|)$ .
[src:huggingface-transformers/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] Some architectures use the transpose of the embedding matrix M as the un-embedding matrix W in order to avoid needing double the amount of embedding-related parameters and to avoid divergence during training.
[src:huggingface-transformers/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] A positional encoding is a fixed-size vector representation of the relative positions of tokens within a sequence: it provides the transformer model with information about *where* the words are in the input sequence.
[src:huggingface-transformers/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] This induces a bias towards the order of the input sequence, so that, for example, the input sequence "man bites dog" is processed differently from "dog bites man".
[src:huggingface-transformers/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] The positional encoding is defined as a function of type $f:\mathbb {R} \to \mathbb {R} ^{d}$ , where d is a positive even integer.
[src:huggingface-transformers/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] Here, N is a free parameter that should be significantly larger than the biggest k that would be input into the positional encoding function.
[src:huggingface-transformers/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] The main reason for using this positional encoding function is that using it, shifts are linear transformations: $f(t+\Delta t)=\mathrm {diag} (f(\Delta t))f(t)$ where $\Delta t\in \mathbb {R}$ is the distance one wishes to shift.
[src:huggingface-transformers/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] This allows the transformer to take any encoded position, and find the encoding of the position n-steps-ahead or n-steps-behind, by a matrix multiplication.
[src:huggingface-transformers/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] By taking a linear sum, any convolution can also be implemented as linear transformations: $\sum _{j}c_{j}f(t+\Delta t_{j})=\left(\sum _{j}c_{j}\,\mathrm {diag} (f(\Delta t_{j}))\right)f(t)$ for any constants $c_{j}$ .
[src:huggingface-transformers/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] This allows the transformer to take any encoded position and find a linear sum of the encoded locations of its neighbors.
[src:huggingface-transformers/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] This sum of encoded positions, when fed into the attention mechanism, would create attention weights on its neighbors, much like what happens in a convolutional neural network language model.
[src:huggingface-transformers/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] In typical implementations, all operations are done over the real numbers, not the complex numbers, but since complex multiplication can be implemented as real 2-by-2 matrix multiplication, this is a mere notational difference.
[src:huggingface-transformers/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] Like earlier seq2seq models, the original transformer model used an **encoder–decoder** architecture.
[src:huggingface-transformers/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] The encoder consists of encoding layers that process all the input tokens together one layer after another, while the decoder consists of decoding layers that iteratively process the encoder's output and the decoder's output tokens so far.
[src:huggingface-transformers/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] The purpose of each encoder layer is to create contextualized representations of the tokens, where each representation corresponds to a token that "mixes" information from other input tokens via self-attention mechanism.
[src:huggingface-transformers/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] Both the encoder and decoder layers have a feed-forward neural network for additional processing of their outputs and contain residual connections and layer normalization steps.
[src:huggingface-transformers/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] These feed-forward layers contain most of the parameters in a transformer model.
[src:huggingface-transformers/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] The feedforward network (FFN) modules in a transformer are 2-layered multilayer perceptrons: $\mathrm {FFN} (x)=\phi (xW^{(1)}+b^{(1)})W^{(2)}+b^{(2)}$ where $W^{(1)}$ and $W^{(2)}$ are weight matrices and $b^{(1)}$ and $b^{(2)}$ are bias vectors, and $\phi$ is its activation function.
[src:huggingface-transformers/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] The original transformer used ReLU activation.
[src:huggingface-transformers/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] The number of neurons in the middle layer is called *intermediate size* (GPT), *filter size* (BERT), or *feedforward size* (BERT).
[src:huggingface-transformers/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] It is typically larger than the embedding size.
[src:huggingface-transformers/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] For example, in both GPT-2 series and BERT series, the intermediate size of a model is 4 times its embedding size: $d_{\text{ffn}}=4d_{\text{emb}}$ .
[src:huggingface-transformers/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] The attention mechanism used in the transformer architecture are scaled dot-product attention units.
[src:huggingface-transformers/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] For each unit, the transformer model learns three weight matrices: the query weights $W^{Q}$ , the key weights $W^{K}$ , and the value weights $W^{V}$ .
[src:huggingface-transformers/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] The module takes three sequences, a query sequence, a key sequence, and a value sequence.
[src:huggingface-transformers/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] The query sequence is a sequence of length $\ell _{\text{seq, query}}$ , and each entry is a vector of dimension $d_{\text{emb, query}}$ .
[src:huggingface-transformers/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] Similarly for the key and value sequences.
[src:huggingface-transformers/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] For each vector $x_{i,{\text{query}}}$ in the query sequence, it is multiplied by a matrix $W^{Q}$ to produce a query vector $q_{i}=x_{i,{\text{query}}}W^{Q}$ .
[src:huggingface-transformers/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] The matrix of all query vectors is the query matrix: $Q=X_{\text{query}}W^{Q}$ Similarly, we construct the key matrix $K=X_{\text{key}}W^{K}$ and the value matrix $V=X_{\text{value}}W^{V}$ .
[src:huggingface-transformers/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] It is usually the case that all $W^{Q},W^{K},W^{V}$ are square matrices, meaning $d_{\text{emb, query}}=d_{\text{query}}$ , etc.
[src:huggingface-transformers/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] Attention weights are calculated using the query and key vectors: the attention weight $a_{ij}$ from token i to token j is the dot product between $q_{i}$ and $k_{j}$ .
[src:huggingface-transformers/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] The attention weights are divided by the square root of the dimension of the key vectors, ${\sqrt {d_{k}}}$ , which stabilizes gradients during training, and passed through a softmax which normalizes the weights.
[src:huggingface-transformers/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] The fact that $W^{Q}$ and $W^{K}$ are different matrices allows attention to be non-symmetric: if token i attends to token j (i.e. $q_{i}\cdot k_{j}$ is large), this does not necessarily mean that token j will attend to token i (i.e. $q_{j}\cdot k_{i}$ could be small).
[src:huggingface-transformers/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] The output of the attention unit for token i is the weighted sum of the value vectors of all tokens, weighted by $a_{ij}$ , the attention from token i to each token.
[src:huggingface-transformers/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] The attention calculation for all tokens can be expressed as one large matrix calculation using the softmax function, which is useful for training due to computational matrix operation optimizations that quickly compute matrix operations.
[src:huggingface-transformers/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] The matrices Q , K and V are defined as the matrices where the i th rows are vectors $q_{i}$ , $k_{i}$ , and $v_{i}$ respectively.
[src:huggingface-transformers/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] where the softmax is applied over each of the rows of the matrix.
[src:huggingface-transformers/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] The number of dimensions in a query vector is *query size* $d_{\text{query}}$ and similarly for the *key size* $d_{\text{key}}$ and *value size* $d_{\text{value}}$ .
[src:huggingface-transformers/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] The output dimension of an attention head is its *head dimension* $d_{\text{head}}$ .
[src:huggingface-transformers/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] The attention mechanism requires the following three equalities to hold: $\ell _{\text{seq, key}}=\ell _{\text{seq, value}},\;d_{\text{query}}=d_{\text{key}},\;d_{\text{value}}=d_{\text{head}}$ but is otherwise unconstrained.
[src:huggingface-transformers/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] If the attention head is used in a self-attention fashion, then $X_{\text{query}}=X_{\text{key}}=X_{\text{value}}$ .
[src:huggingface-transformers/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] If the attention head is used in a cross-attention fashion, then usually $X_{\text{query}}\neq X_{\text{key}}=X_{\text{value}}$ .
[src:huggingface-transformers/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] It is theoretically possible for all three to be different, but that is rarely the case in practice.
[src:huggingface-transformers/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] One set of $\left(W^{Q},W^{K},W^{V}\right)$ matrices is called an *attention head*, and each layer in a transformer model has multiple attention heads.
[src:huggingface-transformers/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] While each attention head attends to the tokens that are relevant to each token, multiple attention heads allow the model to do this for different definitions of "relevance".
[src:huggingface-transformers/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] Specifically, the query and key projection matrices, $W^{Q}$ and $W^{K}$ , which are involved in the attention score computation, defines the "relevance".
[src:huggingface-transformers/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] Meanwhile, the value projection matrix $W^{V}$ , in combination with the part of the output projection matrix $W^{O}$ , determines how the attended tokens influence what information is passed to subsequent layers and ultimately the output logits.
[src:huggingface-transformers/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] In addition, the scope of attention, or the range of token relationships captured by each attention head, can expand as tokens pass through successive layers.
[src:huggingface-transformers/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] This allows the model to capture more complex and long-range dependencies in deeper layers.
[src:huggingface-transformers/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] Many transformer attention heads encode relevance relations that are meaningful to humans.
[src:huggingface-transformers/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] For example, some attention heads can attend mostly to the next word, while others mainly attend from verbs to their direct objects.
[src:huggingface-transformers/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] The computations for each attention head can be performed in parallel, which allows for fast processing.
[src:huggingface-transformers/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] The outputs for the attention layer are concatenated to pass into the feedforward neural network layers.
[src:huggingface-transformers/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] It is theoretically possible for each attention head to have a different head dimension $d_{\text{head}}$ , but that is rarely the case in practice.
[src:huggingface-transformers/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] As an example, in the smallest GPT-2 model, there are only self-attention mechanisms.
[src:huggingface-transformers/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] The transformer architecture is constructed to calculate output tokens iteratively.
[src:huggingface-transformers/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] Assuming $t=0$ refers to the calculation of the first output token $i=0$ , for step $t>0$ , the output token $i=0$ shall remain constant.
[src:huggingface-transformers/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] This ensures properties of the model similar to autoregressive models.
[src:huggingface-transformers/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] Therefore, at every time step t , the calculation for all outputs i should not have access to tokens at position j for $j>=i$ (as it naturally is the case for time step $t=i$ , when tokens $j>t$ are not yet calculated).
[src:huggingface-transformers/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] In words, it means that each token can pay attention to itself, and every token before it, but not any after it.
[src:huggingface-transformers/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] A non-masked attention module can be thought of as a masked attention module where the mask has all entries zero.
[src:huggingface-transformers/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] As an example of an uncommon use of mask matrix, the XLNet considers all masks of the form $PM_{\text{causal}}P^{-1}$ , where P is a random permutation matrix.
[src:huggingface-transformers/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] An encoder consists of an embedding layer, followed by multiple encoder layers.
[src:huggingface-transformers/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] Each encoder layer consists of two major components: a self-attention mechanism and a feed-forward layer.
[src:huggingface-transformers/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] It takes an input as a sequence of input vectors, applies the self-attention mechanism, to produce an intermediate sequence of vectors, then applies the feed-forward layer for each vector individually.
[src:huggingface-transformers/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] where ${\text{FFN}}$ stands for "feed-forward network".
[src:huggingface-transformers/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] We can more succinctly write it as ${\text{EncoderLayer}}(H)={\text{FFN}}({\text{MultiheadAttention}}(H,H,H))$ with the implicit convention that the ${\text{FFN}}$ is applied to each row of the matrix individually.
[src:huggingface-transformers/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] The first encoder layer takes the sequence of input vectors from the embedding layer, producing a sequence of vectors.
[src:huggingface-transformers/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] This sequence of vectors is processed by the second encoder, and so on.
[src:huggingface-transformers/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] The output from the final encoder layer is then used by the decoder.
[src:huggingface-transformers/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] As the encoder processes the entire input all at once, every token can attend to every other token (all-to-all attention), so there is no need for causal masking.
[src:huggingface-transformers/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] A decoder consists of an embedding layer, followed by multiple decoder layers, followed by an un-embedding layer.
[src:huggingface-transformers/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] Each decoder consists of three major components: a causally masked self-attention mechanism, a cross-attention mechanism, and a feed-forward neural network.
[src:huggingface-transformers/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] The decoder functions in a similar fashion to the encoder, but an additional attention mechanism is inserted which instead draws relevant information from the encodings generated by the encoders.
[src:huggingface-transformers/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] This mechanism can also be called the *encoder–decoder attention*.
[src:huggingface-transformers/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] Like the first encoder, the first decoder takes positional information and embeddings of the output sequence as its input, rather than encodings.
[src:huggingface-transformers/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] The transformer must not use the current or future output to predict an output, so the output sequence must be partially masked to prevent this reverse information flow.
[src:huggingface-transformers/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] This allows for autoregressive text generation.
[src:huggingface-transformers/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] For decoding, all-to-all attention is inappropriate, because a token cannot attend to tokens not yet generated.
[src:huggingface-transformers/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] Thus, the self-attention module in the decoder is causally masked.
[src:huggingface-transformers/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] In contrast, the cross-attention mechanism attends to the output vectors of the encoder, which is computed before the decoder starts decoding.
[src:huggingface-transformers/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] Consequently, there is no need for masking in the cross-attention mechanism.
[src:huggingface-transformers/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] Schematically, we have: ${\begin{aligned}H'&={\text{MaskedMultiheadAttention}}(H,H,H)\\{\text{DecoderLayer}}(H)&={\text{FFN}}({\text{MultiheadAttention}}(H',H^{E},H^{E}))\end{aligned}}$ where $H^{E}$ is the matrix with rows being the output vectors from the encoder.
[src:huggingface-transformers/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] The last decoder is followed by a final un-embedding layer to produce the output probabilities over the vocabulary.
[src:huggingface-transformers/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] Then, one of the tokens is sampled according to the probability, and the decoder can be run again to produce the next token, etc., autoregressively generating output text.
[src:huggingface-transformers/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] Each encoder layer contains 2 sublayers: the self-attention and the feedforward network.
[src:huggingface-transformers/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] Each decoder layer contains 3 sublayers: the causally masked self-attention, the cross-attention, and the feedforward network.
[src:huggingface-transformers/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] The final points of detail are the residual connections and layer normalization, (denoted as "LayerNorm", or "LN" in the following), which while conceptually unnecessary, are necessary for numerical stability and convergence.
[src:huggingface-transformers/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] The residual connections are introduced to avoid vanishing gradient issues and stabilize the training process.
[src:huggingface-transformers/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] They can be expressed by $x\mapsto F(x)+x$ , where F is a given component of the transformer.
[src:huggingface-transformers/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] Adding the input x can preserve the input information and avoid issues when the gradient of $F(x)$ is close to zero.
[src:huggingface-transformers/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] Similarly to how the feedforward network modules are applied individually to each vector, the LayerNorm is also applied individually to each vector.
[src:huggingface-transformers/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] There are two common conventions in use: the *post-LN* and the *pre-LN* convention.
[src:huggingface-transformers/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] In the post-LN convention, the output of each sublayer is $\mathrm {LayerNorm} (x+\mathrm {Sublayer} (x))$ where $\mathrm {Sublayer} (x)$ is the function implemented by the sublayer itself.
[src:huggingface-transformers/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] In the pre-LN convention, the output of each sublayer is $x+\mathrm {Sublayer} (\mathrm {LayerNorm} (x))$ The original 2017 transformer used the post-LN convention.
[src:huggingface-transformers/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] It was difficult to train and required careful hyperparameter tuning and a "warm-up" in learning rate, where it starts small and gradually increases.
[src:huggingface-transformers/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] The pre-LN convention, proposed several times in 2018, was found to be easier to train, requiring no warm-up, leading to faster convergence.
[src:huggingface-transformers/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] The transformer architecture, being modular, allows variations.
[src:huggingface-transformers/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] Several common variations are described here.
[src:huggingface-transformers/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] An "encoder-only" transformer applies the encoder to map an input text into a sequence of vectors that represent the input text.
[src:huggingface-transformers/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] This is usually used for text embedding and representation learning for downstream applications.
[src:huggingface-transformers/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] They are less often used currently, as they were found to be not significantly better than training an encoder–decoder transformer, then taking just the encoder.
[src:huggingface-transformers/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] They are also referred to as "all-to-all" or "BERT-like".
[src:huggingface-transformers/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] A "decoder-only" transformer is not literally decoder-only, since without an encoder, the cross-attention mechanism has nothing to attend to.
[src:huggingface-transformers/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] Thus, the decoder layers in a decoder-only transformer is composed of just two sublayers: the causally masked self-attention, and the feedforward network.
[src:huggingface-transformers/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] This is usually used for text generation and instruction following.
[src:huggingface-transformers/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] The models in the GPT series and Chinchilla series are decoder-only.
[src:huggingface-transformers/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] They are also referred to as "autoregressive" or "causal".
[src:huggingface-transformers/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] An "encoder–decoder" transformer is generally the same as the original transformer, with 2 sublayers per encoder layer and 3 sublayers per decoder layer, etc.
[src:huggingface-transformers/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] They might have minor architectural improvements, such as alternative activation functions, changing the location of normalization, etc.
[src:huggingface-transformers/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] This is also usually used for text generation and instruction following.
[src:huggingface-transformers/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] The models in the T5 series are encoder–decoder.
[src:huggingface-transformers/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] A "prefixLM" (prefix language model) is a decoder-only architecture, but with prefix masking, which is different from causal masking.
[src:huggingface-transformers/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] Specifically, it has mask of the form $M_{\text{prefixLM}}={\begin{bmatrix}\mathbf {0} &-\infty \\\mathbf {0} &M_{\text{causal}}\end{bmatrix}}$ where the first columns correspond to the "prefix", and the subsequent columns correspond to the autoregressively generated text based on the prefix.
[src:huggingface-transformers/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] They resemble encoder–decoder models, but has less "sparsity".
[src:huggingface-transformers/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] Such models are rarely used, though they are cited as theoretical possibilities and benchmarked comparisons.
[src:huggingface-transformers/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] For example, in 2020, Google Translate replaced the previous RNN-encoder–RNN-decoder model with a transformer-encoder–RNN-decoder model, as transformer-based decoders did not appear to significantly increase quality unlike the encoder, while the RNN decoder was much faster.
[src:huggingface-transformers/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] The original transformer uses ReLU activation function.
[src:huggingface-transformers/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] Other activation functions were developed.
[src:huggingface-transformers/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] The Llama series and PaLM used SwiGLU; both GPT-1 and BERT used GELU.
[src:huggingface-transformers/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] Alternative activation functions are often used in combination with Gated Linear Units in the feedforward module.
[src:huggingface-transformers/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] The normalization used in the transformer can be different from LayerNorm.
[src:huggingface-transformers/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] One example is RMSNorm which is used in the Llama series.
[src:huggingface-transformers/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] Other examples include ScaleNorm and FixNorm.
[src:huggingface-transformers/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] Transformers may use other positional encoding methods than sinusoidal.
[src:huggingface-transformers/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] The original transformer paper reported using a learned positional encoding, but finding it not superior to the sinusoidal one.
[src:huggingface-transformers/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] Later, found that causal masking itself provides enough signal to a transformer decoder that it can learn to implicitly perform absolute positional encoding without the positional encoding module.
[src:huggingface-transformers/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] Then the RoPE encoding is applied to each pair of coordinates.
[src:huggingface-transformers/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] The benefit of RoPE is that the dot-product between two vectors depends on their relative location only: ${\text{RoPE}}{\big (}x,m{\big )}^{T}{\text{RoPE}}{\big (}y,n{\big )}={\text{RoPE}}{\big (}x,m+k{\big )}^{T}{\text{RoPE}}{\big (}y,n+k{\big )}$ for any integer k .
[src:huggingface-transformers/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] ALiBi (Attention with Linear Biases) is not a *replacement* for the positional encoder on the original transformer.
[src:huggingface-transformers/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] Instead, it is an *additional* positional encoder that is directly plugged into the attention mechanism.
[src:huggingface-transformers/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] The idea being that the linear bias matrix is a softened mask.
[src:huggingface-transformers/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] Just as 0 represent full attention paid, and $-\infty$ represents no attention paid, the linear bias matrix increases attention paid in one direction and decreases attention paid in the other direction.
[src:huggingface-transformers/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] ALiBi allows pretraining on short context windows, then fine-tuning on longer context windows.
[src:huggingface-transformers/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] Since it is directly plugged into the attention mechanism, it can be combined with any positional encoder that is plugged into the "bottom" of the entire network (which is where the sinusoidal encoder on the original transformer, as well as RoPE and many others, are located).
[src:huggingface-transformers/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] Relative Position Encodings is similar to ALiBi, but more generic: ${\begin{aligned}{\text{Attention}}(Q,K,V)={\text{softmax}}\left({\frac {QK^{\mathrm {T} }}{\sqrt {d_{k}}}}+B\right)V\end{aligned}}$ where B is a Toeplitz matrix, that is, $B_{i,j}=B_{i',j'}$ whenever $i-j=i'-j'$ .
[src:huggingface-transformers/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] This is contrasted with the original sinusoidal positional encoding, which is an "absolute positional encoding".
[src:huggingface-transformers/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] The transformer model has been implemented in standard deep learning frameworks such as TensorFlow and PyTorch.
[src:huggingface-transformers/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] *Transformers* is a library produced by Hugging Face that supplies transformer-based architectures and pretrained models.
[src:huggingface-transformers/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] When an autoregressive transformer is used for inference, such as generating text, the query vector is different at each step, but the already-computed key and value vectors are always the same.
[src:huggingface-transformers/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] The **KV caching** method saves the computed key and value vectors at each attention block, so that they are not recomputed at each new token.
[src:huggingface-transformers/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] PagedAttention applies memory paging to KV caching.
[src:huggingface-transformers/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] If a transformer is used with a baked-in prompt, such as ["You are a customer support agent..."], then the key and value vectors can be computed for the prompt, and saved on disk.
[src:huggingface-transformers/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] The saving in compute is significant when the model is used for many short real-time interactions, such as in online chatbots.
[src:huggingface-transformers/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] In general, when a user uses an autoregressive transformer to generate a continuation to a sequence of tokens, the model would first perform a forward-pass on this sequence, whereby the KV caches over this sequence are computed.
[src:huggingface-transformers/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] Hyperscalers serving large Transformer models may use **disaggregated inference**, wherein prefilling and decoding are performed on separately specialized hardware.
[src:huggingface-transformers/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] FlashAttention is an algorithm that implements the transformer attention mechanism efficiently on a GPU.
[src:huggingface-transformers/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] It is a communication-avoiding algorithm that performs matrix multiplications in blocks, such that each block fits within the cache of a GPU, and by careful management of the blocks it minimizes data copying between GPU caches (as data movement is slow).
[src:huggingface-transformers/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] The FlashAttention method is a communication-avoiding algorithm that fuses these operations into a single loop, increasing the arithmetic intensity.
[src:huggingface-transformers/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] In practice, FlashAttention operates over multiple queries and keys per loop iteration, in a similar way as blocked matrix multiplication.
[src:huggingface-transformers/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] If backpropagation is needed, then the output vectors and the intermediate arrays $[m_{1},\dots ,m_{N}],[\ell _{1},\dots ,\ell _{N}]$ are cached, and during the backward pass, attention matrices are rematerialized from these, making it a form of gradient checkpointing.
[src:huggingface-transformers/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] An improved version, FlashAttention-2, was developed to cater to the rising demand for language models capable of handling longer context lengths.
[src:huggingface-transformers/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] It offers enhancements in work partitioning and parallelism, enabling it to achieve up to 230 TFLOPs/s on A100 GPUs (FP16/BF16), a 2x speed increase over the original FlashAttention.
[src:huggingface-transformers/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] Key advancements in FlashAttention-2 include the reduction of non-matmul FLOPs, improved parallelism over the sequence length dimension, better work partitioning between GPU warps, and added support for head dimensions up to 256 and multi-query attention (MQA) and grouped-query attention (GQA).
[src:huggingface-transformers/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] Benchmarks revealed FlashAttention-2 to be up to 2x faster than FlashAttention and up to 9x faster than a standard attention implementation in PyTorch.
[src:huggingface-transformers/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] Future developments include optimization for new hardware like H100 GPUs and new data types like FP8.
[src:huggingface-transformers/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] FlashAttention-4 focuses on pipelining to increase instruction throughput, and was developed to perform particularly well on Blackwell GPUs.
[src:huggingface-transformers/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] Multi-Query Attention changes the Multihead Attention mechanism.
[src:huggingface-transformers/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] This has a neutral effect on model quality and training speed, but increases inference speed.
[src:huggingface-transformers/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] More generally, grouped-query attention (GQA) partitions attention heads into groups, each of which shares the key-value pair.
[src:huggingface-transformers/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] MQA is GQA with one group, while standard Multihead Attention is GQA with the maximal number of groups.
[src:huggingface-transformers/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] Multihead Latent Attention (MLA) is a low-rank approximation to standard MHA.
[src:huggingface-transformers/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] Specifically, each hidden vector, before entering the attention mechanism, is first projected to two low-dimensional spaces ("latent space"), one for query and one for key-value (KV vector).
[src:huggingface-transformers/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] This design minimizes the KV cache, as only the low-dimensional KV vector needs to be cached.
[src:huggingface-transformers/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] Speculative decoding is a method to accelerate token decoding.
[src:huggingface-transformers/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] Similarly to speculative execution in CPUs, future tokens are computed quickly, then verified.
[src:huggingface-transformers/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] If the quickly computed tokens are incorrect, they are discarded and computed slowly.
[src:huggingface-transformers/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] The key factor in speculative decoding is that a transformer decoder can verify faster than it can decode, in the following sense.
[src:huggingface-transformers/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] Suppose we have two transformer models like GPT-3 and GPT-3-small, both with a context window size of 512.
[src:huggingface-transformers/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] To generate an entire context window autoregressively with greedy decoding with GPT-3, it must be run for 512 times, each time generating a token $x_{1},x_{2},...,x_{512}$ , taking time $512T_{\text{GPT-3}}$ .
[src:huggingface-transformers/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] However, if we had some educated guess for the values of these tokens, we could verify all of them in parallel, in one run of the model, by checking that each $x_{t}$ is indeed the token with the largest log-likelihood in the t -th output.
[src:huggingface-transformers/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] In speculative decoding, a smaller model or some other simple heuristic is used to generate a few speculative tokens that are subsequently verified by the larger model.
[src:huggingface-transformers/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] These tokens are then run through the larger GPT-3 in one go.
[src:huggingface-transformers/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] Suppose that ${\tilde {x}}_{1}$ and ${\tilde {x}}_{2}$ are verified by GPT-3 as what it would have picked, then those are kept, but ${\tilde {x}}_{3}$ is not, so ${\tilde {x}}_{3},{\tilde {x}}_{4}$ are discarded, and GPT-3 is run on those.
[src:huggingface-transformers/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] For non-greedy decoding, similar ideas apply, except the speculative tokens are accepted or rejected stochastically, in a way that guarantees the final output distribution is the same as if speculative decoding was not used.
[src:huggingface-transformers/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] In Multi-Token Prediction, a single forward pass creates a final embedding vector, which then is un-embedded into a token probability.
[src:huggingface-transformers/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] However, that vector can then be further processed by another transformer block to predict the *next* token, and so on for arbitrarily many steps into the future.
[src:huggingface-transformers/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] This trades off accuracy for speed, since each new token costs just one more transformer block, rather than the entire stack.
[src:huggingface-transformers/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] Training transformer-based architectures can be expensive, especially for long inputs.
[src:huggingface-transformers/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] Many methods have been developed to attempt to address the issue.
[src:huggingface-transformers/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] In the image domain, Swin transformer is an efficient architecture that performs attention inside shifting windows.
[src:huggingface-transformers/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] In the audio domain, SepTr decouples the attention in time and frequency domains.
[src:huggingface-transformers/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] *Long Range Arena* (2020) is a standard benchmark for comparing the behavior of transformer architectures over long inputs.
[src:huggingface-transformers/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] The standard attention graph is either all-to-all or causal, both of which scales as $O(N^{2})$ where N is the number of tokens in a sequence.
[src:huggingface-transformers/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] Reformer (2020) reduces the computational load from $O(N^{2})$ to $O(N\ln N)$ by using locality-sensitive hashing and reversible layers.
[src:huggingface-transformers/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] Sparse attention uses attention graphs that grows slower than $O(N^{2})$ .
[src:huggingface-transformers/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] For example, BigBird (2020) uses random small-world networks which grows as $O(N)$ .
[src:huggingface-transformers/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] Ordinary transformers require a memory size that is quadratic in the size of the context window.
[src:huggingface-transformers/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] Attention-free transformers reduce this to a linear dependence while still retaining the advantages of a transformer by linking the key to the value.
[src:huggingface-transformers/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] Similarly for multiple queries, and for multihead attention.
[src:huggingface-transformers/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] This approximation can be computed in linear time, as we can compute the matrix $\varphi (k_{i})v_{i}^{T}$ first, then multiply it with the query.
[src:huggingface-transformers/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] Transformers can also be used/adapted for modalities (input or output) beyond just text, usually by finding a way to "tokenize" the modality.
[src:huggingface-transformers/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] Multimodal models can either be trained from scratch, or by finetuning.
[src:huggingface-transformers/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] A 2022 study found that transformers pretrained only on natural language can be finetuned on only 0.03% of parameters and become competitive with LSTMs on a variety of logical and visual tasks, demonstrating transfer learning.
[src:huggingface-transformers/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] The LLaVA was a vision-language model composed of a language model (Vicuna-13B) and a vision model (ViT-L/14), connected by a linear layer.
[src:huggingface-transformers/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] Vision transformers adapt the transformer to computer vision by breaking down input images as a series of patches, turning them into vectors, and treating them like embedding vector of tokens in a standard transformer.
[src:huggingface-transformers/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] Conformer and later Whisper follow the same pattern for speech recognition, first turning the speech signal into a spectrogram, which is then treated like an image, i.e. broken down into a series of patches, turned into vectors and treated like embedding vector of tokens in a standard transformer.
[src:huggingface-transformers/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] Perceivers are a variant of transformers designed for multimodality.
[src:huggingface-transformers/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] For image generation, notable architectures are DALL-E 1 (2021), Parti (2022), Phenaki (2023), and Muse (2023).
[src:huggingface-transformers/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] Unlike later models, DALL-E is not a diffusion model.
[src:huggingface-transformers/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] Instead, it uses a decoder-only transformer that autoregressively generates a text, followed by the token representation of an image, which is then converted by a variational autoencoder to an image.
[src:huggingface-transformers/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] Parti is an encoder–decoder transformer, where the encoder processes a text prompt, and the decoder generates a token representation of an image.
[src:huggingface-transformers/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] Muse is an encoder-only transformer that is trained to predict masked image tokens from unmasked image tokens.
[src:huggingface-transformers/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] During generation, all input tokens are masked, and the highest-confidence predictions are included for the next iteration, until all tokens are predicted.
[src:huggingface-transformers/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] It is a bidirectional masked transformer conditioned on pre-computed text tokens.
[src:huggingface-transformers/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] The generated tokens are then decoded to a video.
[src:huggingface-transformers/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] The transformer has had great success in natural language processing (NLP).
